00:08:18.310 --> 00:08:22.240
some of the background
information.

00:08:22.240 --> 00:08:26.270
So Lois is going
to just start us

00:08:26.270 --> 00:08:30.430
out with getting the framework.

00:08:30.430 --> 00:08:31.730
&gt;&gt; Lois Bridges: OK.

00:08:31.730 --> 00:08:37.760
Well, on your table as Lesley
said you should see the sixth

00:08:37.760 --> 00:08:50.740
edition of the Scholastic' "Kid
and Family Reading Report".

00:08:50.740 --> 00:08:53.890
This comes out every other year.

00:08:53.890 --> 00:08:55.630
And I'm just going
to highlight a few

00:08:55.630 --> 00:08:56.930
of the key findings for you.

00:08:56.930 --> 00:08:58.230
Let's see.

00:08:58.230 --> 00:09:03.900
Let's automatically go-- I
just want to mention that if

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:11.870
for the sixth edition, we
survey 2,700 families and kids,

00:09:11.870 --> 00:09:17.600
it is a nationally
representative sample

00:09:17.600 --> 00:09:21.320
and the people that we
interview didn't know

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:24.340
that we were with Scholastic.

00:09:24.340 --> 00:09:29.650
And the idea behind this
report really is to try

00:09:29.650 --> 00:09:34.040
to understand the attitudes
and the behaviors of families

00:09:34.040 --> 00:09:35.670
as they connect with reading.

00:09:35.670 --> 00:09:37.780
So the first thing I want

00:09:37.780 --> 00:09:40.920
to mention is the critical
importance of choice.

00:09:40.920 --> 00:09:45.170
It turns out that choice,
the books that we choose

00:09:45.170 --> 00:09:48.130
to read reflect your agency
and identity as a reader.

00:09:48.130 --> 00:09:49.430
And I think that all
makes sense to us.

00:09:49.430 --> 00:09:50.730
Those of us with rich reading
lives have a clear sense

00:09:50.730 --> 00:09:52.030
of the kinds of books
that we like to read,

00:09:52.030 --> 00:09:53.330
the authors that we
love, the genres we like.

00:09:53.330 --> 00:09:54.630
And that's a big part
of discovering yourself

00:09:54.630 --> 00:09:55.930
as a leader, as a young child.

00:09:55.930 --> 00:09:57.230
So we were happy to see that
when it comes to reading

00:09:57.230 --> 00:09:58.530
for fun, 63% of kids
say they get

00:09:58.530 --> 00:09:59.830
to choose their books for fun.

00:09:59.830 --> 00:10:06.180
Let me turn to my-- And in
response to the statement--

00:10:06.180 --> 00:10:07.480
oops, [inaudible],
lined up with the--

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:14.810
I am more likely to finish
reading a book that I picked

00:10:14.810 --> 00:10:18.210
out myself, 88% say yes.

00:10:18.210 --> 00:10:20.910
If I get to choose the book
myself I'm more interested in it

00:10:20.910 --> 00:10:24.500
and I'm going to
finish reading it.

00:10:24.500 --> 00:10:28.590
OK. Just a quick word about the
disparity of books in the home

00:10:28.590 --> 00:10:32.020
and Stephen will likely
have different statistics,

00:10:32.020 --> 00:10:33.630
it'll be interesting.

00:10:33.630 --> 00:10:37.450
Scholastics found that the
average number of books

00:10:37.450 --> 00:10:45.750
in the home were 104 but there
are almost twice as many books

00:10:45.750 --> 00:10:50.830
in the homes of frequent readers
versus infrequent readers.

00:10:50.830 --> 00:10:52.350
And by frequent readers,

00:10:52.350 --> 00:10:55.740
I mean kids who are reading
every single day five

00:10:55.740 --> 00:11:02.900
to seven days a week, moderate
readers one to four days a week

00:11:02.900 --> 00:11:06.510
and infrequent readers
less than a day a week.

00:11:06.510 --> 00:11:11.100
So you can see that-- oh
and one thing I wanted

00:11:11.100 --> 00:11:13.980
to mention is how did the books
get in the home to begin with?

00:11:13.980 --> 00:11:19.350
And the number one reason is
because kids ask for the books.

00:11:19.350 --> 00:11:21.980
So you can see that if
you're a frequent reader,

00:11:21.980 --> 00:11:26.360
if you have a sense of yourself
as a reader you know what books

00:11:26.360 --> 00:11:27.810
to ask your parents for.

00:11:27.810 --> 00:11:31.350
But and this of course
as Stephen will have lots

00:11:31.350 --> 00:11:35.540
of information about this,
if you have the means

00:11:35.540 --> 00:11:38.930
to purchase the books,
or you have access

00:11:38.930 --> 00:11:42.290
to a public library that's
open, it's easier for you

00:11:42.290 --> 00:11:48.420
to bring those books
into your home.

00:11:48.420 --> 00:11:53.950
So again, sorry, got wind up,

00:11:53.950 --> 00:11:57.820
reading frequency
is largely steady.

00:11:57.820 --> 00:11:59.700
There's a slight drop

00:11:59.700 --> 00:12:04.550
in frequent readers
from 2010 to 2016.

00:12:04.550 --> 00:12:05.850
That's good news.

00:12:05.850 --> 00:12:08.130
We here so much about how
kids no longer like to read.

00:12:08.130 --> 00:12:10.200
And that's not what
we found at all.

00:12:10.200 --> 00:12:16.450
In 2010, maybe 37% of
kids thought that reading

00:12:16.450 --> 00:12:18.300
for fun was very important.

00:12:18.300 --> 00:12:23.610
It did drop slightly to
32% but for the most part,

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:26.700
kids are reading
and enjoy reading.

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:35.130
What about kids use on
the importance of reading.

00:12:35.130 --> 00:12:37.540
Again, it's holding steady.

00:12:37.540 --> 00:12:46.460
In fact it even went
up a bit in 2010,

00:12:46.460 --> 00:12:53.190
only 50% thought
it was important

00:12:53.190 --> 00:13:02.760
and 2016 that went up to 55%.

00:13:02.760 --> 00:13:04.140
So that' good.

00:13:04.140 --> 00:13:13.640
And I will say that we are
keeping our eye on younger teens

00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:18.160
because we did notice that
in terms of their interest

00:13:18.160 --> 00:13:25.190
in reading books for fun,
there has been a drop.

00:13:25.190 --> 00:13:32.270
In 2010, 61% enjoyed
reading books for fun.

00:13:32.270 --> 00:13:39.270
And that dropped to 50% in 2016.

00:13:39.270 --> 00:13:41.580
So we're going to keep our eye--

00:13:41.580 --> 00:13:44.160
we're actually in a process
right now putting together

00:13:44.160 --> 00:13:45.460
another report.

00:13:45.460 --> 00:13:48.840
And that's a group we really
want to check in with.

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:51.640
OK. Now, this is
something interesting.

00:13:51.640 --> 00:13:55.760
Fifty-seven percent
of kids, age six to 17

00:13:55.760 --> 00:13:59.270
who are infrequent readers
say it's hard for them

00:13:59.270 --> 00:14:02.870
to find books they like to read.

00:14:02.870 --> 00:14:06.680
And that makes sense
if you don't read,

00:14:06.680 --> 00:14:07.980
you don't necessarily--

00:14:07.980 --> 00:14:13.280
you haven't necessarily
established an identity

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:14.580
as a reader.

00:14:14.580 --> 00:14:15.880
And so, you-- you know, it's
hard for you to find books

00:14:15.880 --> 00:14:17.180
that you like to read.

00:14:17.180 --> 00:14:24.170
And I'm reminded of a quote I
like a lot from James Paterson.

00:14:24.170 --> 00:14:27.000
You may recognized him as--

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:31.090
actually, I think he
is the number one--

00:14:31.090 --> 00:14:35.300
he has more books on the New
York Times' Best Seller list

00:14:35.300 --> 00:14:37.870
than any other author ever.

00:14:37.870 --> 00:14:41.060
And he said that
there is no such thing

00:14:41.060 --> 00:14:43.890
as a kid who hates reading.

00:14:43.890 --> 00:14:48.290
There are kids who love
to read and there are kids

00:14:48.290 --> 00:14:50.980
who just haven't found
the right book yet.

00:14:50.980 --> 00:14:54.720
And so, it's our responsibility

00:14:54.720 --> 00:14:56.660
to help kids find
the right books.

