00:28:49.070 --> 00:28:52.430
From library after library,
the house was filled

00:28:52.430 --> 00:28:55.100
with fugitive books
from all over the city.

00:28:55.100 --> 00:28:57.290
Elizabeth said that
when she was in school,

00:28:57.290 --> 00:28:59.130
she played hockey
most of the time.

00:28:59.130 --> 00:29:00.610
She only went to
school toward the end,

00:29:00.610 --> 00:29:03.050
so she could see what was
on the test and she said,

00:29:03.050 --> 00:29:06.860
this is how I sneak by
from grade to grade.

00:29:06.860 --> 00:29:09.320
Geoffrey Canada, Harvard
children's-- how--

00:29:09.320 --> 00:29:11.690
Harlem Children's
Zone, same story.

00:29:11.690 --> 00:29:14.270
He got books from a buddy
of his and from his mom,

00:29:14.270 --> 00:29:19.330
they were the source and this is
why he said he did OK in school.

00:29:19.330 --> 00:29:24.980
So reading gives you better
language, gives you knowledge

00:29:24.980 --> 00:29:28.060
and it also gives you what
we call habits of mind.

00:29:28.060 --> 00:29:30.930
This is a stuff that's just come
out in the last couple of years,

00:29:30.930 --> 00:29:33.400
big article about it
in Scientific American,

00:29:33.400 --> 00:29:34.970
I was very happy to see that.

00:29:34.970 --> 00:29:38.960
People who read more have
more empathy for others.

00:29:38.960 --> 00:29:40.690
Fiction reading is
what does that.

00:29:40.690 --> 00:29:43.020
You go through other
people's experiences

00:29:43.020 --> 00:29:45.490
and you see the world
for how complex it is.

00:29:45.490 --> 00:29:47.650
You don't rush for
simple solutions.

00:29:47.650 --> 00:29:50.340
With that in mind, let
me show you a letter

00:29:50.340 --> 00:29:52.540
to the editor that I published.

00:29:52.540 --> 00:29:57.080
In the Washington Post last
month, I was amazed it got in.

00:29:57.080 --> 00:30:00.530
They had article after article
about Donald Trump's spelling.

00:30:00.530 --> 00:30:02.940
And they blamed it
on poor proofreading,

00:30:02.940 --> 00:30:04.240
two articles in a row.

00:30:04.240 --> 00:30:06.430
And one, you know,
they have one--

00:30:06.430 --> 00:30:09.050
people said why you're
picking on him, blah, blah.

00:30:09.050 --> 00:30:10.800
Well, here's my letter.

00:30:10.800 --> 00:30:13.280
My letter says, poor
spelling is indication

00:30:13.280 --> 00:30:14.650
of more serious problems.

00:30:14.650 --> 00:30:18.230
Mr. Trump's mistakes
reflect problems deeper

00:30:18.230 --> 00:30:20.020
than a failure to proofread.

00:30:20.020 --> 00:30:22.710
My research shows, poor
spelling is often the result

00:30:22.710 --> 00:30:24.800
of not having a reading
habit and those

00:30:24.800 --> 00:30:27.530
who read more know a lot more
about history and science.

00:30:27.530 --> 00:30:30.500
They have greater empathy
with other and understand

00:30:30.500 --> 00:30:32.460
that the world is complex.

00:30:32.460 --> 00:30:35.730
Mr. Trump is a perfect
example of a nonreader.

00:30:35.730 --> 00:30:37.310
I rest my case.

00:30:37.310 --> 00:30:39.050
You're supposed to burst
under wild applause.

00:30:39.050 --> 00:30:41.140
I'm sorry, you've missed that.

00:30:41.140 --> 00:30:42.440
Come on, give me a break here.

00:30:42.440 --> 00:30:43.740
OK [applause].

00:30:43.740 --> 00:30:46.830
All right.

00:30:46.830 --> 00:30:51.540
I've been writing him
nearly everyday on Twitter,

00:30:51.540 --> 00:30:54.670
and Betsy Devos constantly.

00:30:54.670 --> 00:30:58.450
It's going nowhere but at
least my followers see it.

00:30:58.450 --> 00:31:02.320
To summarize all these
into bigger picture,

00:31:02.320 --> 00:31:06.780
I claim poverty means
less access, less access,

00:31:06.780 --> 00:31:09.760
less reading and more
reading more literacy.

00:31:09.760 --> 00:31:13.380
The last set of studies I'm
going to show you, I think,

00:31:13.380 --> 00:31:15.890
are the most important
studies I've ever been part of.

00:31:15.890 --> 00:31:18.150
I did-- I was part
of a research team

00:31:18.150 --> 00:31:21.550
with my two former students
Syying Lee in Taiwan

00:31:21.550 --> 00:31:24.010
and Jeff McQuillan
in the United States.

00:31:24.010 --> 00:31:26.330
We looked at predictors
of both the NAEP exam

00:31:26.330 --> 00:31:28.690
and the PIRLS exam.

00:31:28.690 --> 00:31:31.330
These are standardized test
giving the lots of kids.

00:31:31.330 --> 00:31:34.150
And we did what we called
multivariate analysis,

00:31:34.150 --> 00:31:35.450
which is [inaudible].

00:31:35.450 --> 00:31:37.700
It's called Multiple Regression.

00:31:37.700 --> 00:31:40.580
For both of you who remember
you statistics class,

00:31:40.580 --> 00:31:42.310
here's what we can do in this.

00:31:42.310 --> 00:31:44.250
We can look at the
influence of predictors

00:31:44.250 --> 00:31:46.650
as if they're not correlated
as if they're independent

00:31:46.650 --> 00:31:48.270
with statistical magic.

00:31:48.270 --> 00:31:52.230
On the NAEP examination,
poverty, yes,

00:31:52.230 --> 00:31:54.450
high poverty means
lower NAEP scores,

00:31:54.450 --> 00:31:56.710
no question, very strong.

00:31:56.710 --> 00:32:00.780
If you put into the equation,
access to books, public library

00:32:00.780 --> 00:32:03.150
and school library,
the access factor

00:32:03.150 --> 00:32:06.220
in the first studies we
did were actually stronger.

00:32:06.220 --> 00:32:10.630
Access can make up for
the effective poverty.

00:32:10.630 --> 00:32:12.630
You should be staring
open mouth.

00:32:12.630 --> 00:32:14.450
OK. This is amazing.

00:32:14.450 --> 00:32:17.650
We did the same and then
we replicated our results.

00:32:17.650 --> 00:32:21.110
We did the same thing with this
international PIRLS test given

00:32:21.110 --> 00:32:23.710
to kids in 40 countries
over the world played

00:32:23.710 --> 00:32:25.300
up in the newspapers.

00:32:25.300 --> 00:32:27.410
[Inaudible] the results
should be published

00:32:27.410 --> 00:32:30.230
in the sports section, all
right, who won, et cetera.

00:32:30.230 --> 00:32:33.990
Well, we found the same
results over and over again.

00:32:33.990 --> 00:32:37.110
The biggest predictor,
of course, poverty.

00:32:37.110 --> 00:32:42.340
If you add a library, a school
library of 500 books, nearly,

00:32:42.340 --> 00:32:45.590
as strong as the
effect of poverty.

00:32:45.590 --> 00:32:48.070
In other words, it helps
balance the effect.

00:32:48.070 --> 00:32:49.790
Kids in high poverty
don't read well

00:32:49.790 --> 00:32:51.710
because they don't
have access to books.

00:32:51.710 --> 00:32:54.840
You have the school library,
they read a lot better.

00:32:54.840 --> 00:32:58.390
We also found in all our studies
that the effect of instruction

00:32:58.390 --> 00:32:59.980
of various kinds,
early instruction,

00:32:59.980 --> 00:33:03.490
late instruction was
either negative or nothing.

00:33:03.490 --> 00:33:06.710
This is what's counted.

00:33:06.710 --> 00:33:10.050
Finally, a few more random
facts that support all these.

00:33:10.050 --> 00:33:11.580
When you statistically--

00:33:11.580 --> 00:33:15.440
When researchers statistically
control for the effect

00:33:15.440 --> 00:33:19.270
of poverty, American
test scores are nearly

00:33:19.270 --> 00:33:20.910
at the top of the world.

00:33:20.910 --> 00:33:23.770
There's nothing wrong
with our teachers.

00:33:23.770 --> 00:33:25.370
We can always improve,
we know that.

00:33:25.370 --> 00:33:28.860
Nothing wrong with our schools,
it's not unions, it is poverty

00:33:28.860 --> 00:33:31.000
and lack of access to books.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:32.830
So what can we do about this?

00:33:32.830 --> 00:33:34.130
Two things.

00:33:34.130 --> 00:33:35.430
And I think they're
both wonderful.

00:33:35.430 --> 00:33:37.180
The first one is what
Dr. King recommended,

00:33:37.180 --> 00:33:40.200
which is not radical right
or left wing communism,

00:33:40.200 --> 00:33:45.240
it's common sense, reduce and
eventually eliminate poverty.

00:33:45.240 --> 00:33:47.390
This means full employment
at way--

00:33:47.390 --> 00:33:51.510
jobs that pay a decent wage
that people can live from.

00:33:51.510 --> 00:33:52.810
This is radical.

00:33:52.810 --> 00:33:54.110
No, it isn't.

00:33:54.110 --> 00:33:56.300
Number two, until that
happens, protect children

00:33:56.300 --> 00:33:59.760
from the impact of poverty.

00:33:59.760 --> 00:34:03.270
That means three things in my
opinion, at least, number one,

00:34:03.270 --> 00:34:06.380
food deprivation,
good breakfast,

00:34:06.380 --> 00:34:09.880
good lunch in school and,
of course, espresso machine

00:34:09.880 --> 00:34:11.670
in the teacher's
lounge [laughter].

00:34:11.670 --> 00:34:15.450
Yes. OK. Number two,
health care.

00:34:15.450 --> 00:34:20.780
David Berliner, his studies high
income areas have more school

00:34:20.780 --> 00:34:23.420
nurses per child than
low income schools.

00:34:23.420 --> 00:34:24.720
You all know this.

00:34:24.720 --> 00:34:27.720
And it's not the crazy things,
it's not the exotic things,

00:34:27.720 --> 00:34:30.050
it's things like
getting dental care,

00:34:30.050 --> 00:34:32.690
making sure that kids have
glasses when they need them.

00:34:32.690 --> 00:34:35.070
The ordinary every day stuff.

00:34:35.070 --> 00:34:39.870
Number three, invest in school
libraries and school librarians

00:34:39.870 --> 00:34:43.440
which independently show
better results for literacy.

00:34:43.440 --> 00:34:46.360
Our hero here Keith.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:54.030
I want to mention two heroes,
one is Keith Curry Lance.

00:34:54.030 --> 00:34:55.330
You know who he is?

00:34:55.330 --> 00:34:57.280
Check out Keith Curry Lance, OK?

00:34:57.280 --> 00:34:59.070
He is-- I call him
the "Golden Boy

00:34:59.070 --> 00:35:01.750
of the American School
Library, so with good reason.

00:35:01.750 --> 00:35:03.250
He's been doing this
stuff for years

00:35:03.250 --> 00:35:05.710
and it's all very
interesting research.

00:35:05.710 --> 00:35:10.210
The other hero, commenting on
Read-Aloud is Jim Trelease,

00:35:10.210 --> 00:35:13.050
the Read-Aloud handbook.

00:35:13.050 --> 00:35:17.830
My-- Let me tell me about
my mom and Jim Trelease, OK?

00:35:17.830 --> 00:35:20.650
My mom and I had a
perfect relationship.

00:35:20.650 --> 00:35:22.220
Let me tell you, I
am my mother's son,

00:35:22.220 --> 00:35:23.540
you know, I love that.

00:35:23.540 --> 00:35:25.970
But, I'm my mother's
son, no question.

00:35:25.970 --> 00:35:27.760
She thought I was wonderful.

00:35:27.760 --> 00:35:29.450
She loved the way
I gave speeches.

00:35:29.450 --> 00:35:30.850
She loved my writing.

00:35:30.850 --> 00:35:33.230
I had a copy of the
riddle out handbook

00:35:33.230 --> 00:35:35.070
in the office and
she borrowed it.

00:35:35.070 --> 00:35:37.460
She gave it back to me and
you know what she said?

00:35:37.460 --> 00:35:41.110
Stephen, why can't you
write like this [laughter]?

00:35:41.110 --> 00:35:42.560
I wish I could.

00:35:42.560 --> 00:35:45.550
This guy has done more good
for libraries and reading

00:35:45.550 --> 00:35:46.960
than any single person.

00:35:46.960 --> 00:35:48.910
And we need to get
people to read his book.

00:35:48.910 --> 00:35:50.210
It's still wonderful.

00:35:50.210 --> 00:35:53.670
Post script as Lois
mentioned, there is no evidence

00:35:53.670 --> 00:35:55.290
for serious decline in reading.

00:35:55.290 --> 00:35:57.590
Everybody keeps saying it,
close look at the data.

00:35:57.590 --> 00:36:00.280
You see little blips
here and there.

00:36:00.280 --> 00:36:03.720
Here's my analysis which
I responded to the feds

00:36:03.720 --> 00:36:06.740
on these several times when
they have this, you know,

00:36:06.740 --> 00:36:09.600
horrible articles about how
kids aren't reading anymore,

00:36:09.600 --> 00:36:10.900
et cetera.

00:36:10.900 --> 00:36:12.470
Here's a comparison.

00:36:12.470 --> 00:36:17.560
One of many we've done comparing
in 1946 report and a 2010 report

00:36:17.560 --> 00:36:20.550
on how many minutes a
day kids are reading.

00:36:20.550 --> 00:36:23.110
Kids are reading, people
are reading the same number

00:36:23.110 --> 00:36:27.980
of books, minutes per day of
reading as they did in 1945.

00:36:27.980 --> 00:36:33.040
Fewer magazines and newspapers
everybody knows this, OK,

00:36:33.040 --> 00:36:39.470
but more websites which we now
have, total just about the same.

00:36:39.470 --> 00:36:43.490
There has been no serious
decline in reading.

00:36:43.490 --> 00:36:46.470
The problem is poverty.

00:36:46.470 --> 00:36:48.270
Thank you.

00:36:48.270 --> 00:36:59.010
[ Applause ]

00:36:59.010 --> 00:37:00.310
&gt;&gt; Loreiene Roy: [Inaudible].

00:37:00.310 --> 00:37:07.120
Hello. So reading across tribal
nations is rather impossible

00:37:07.120 --> 00:37:11.870
really to talk about these 560
federally recognized tribes,

00:37:11.870 --> 00:37:16.280
a 100 plus tribes recognized
by state governments,

00:37:16.280 --> 00:37:19.050
just as difficult,
if not impossible

00:37:19.050 --> 00:37:21.720
to generalize about
Indian people.

00:37:21.720 --> 00:37:24.970
It's also difficult and not
impossible to take one topic

00:37:24.970 --> 00:37:26.990
or issue such as literacy

00:37:26.990 --> 00:37:28.750
and describe how
it's being addressed

00:37:28.750 --> 00:37:30.740
across hundreds of nations.

00:37:30.740 --> 00:37:34.490
That said, let's do it any way.

00:37:34.490 --> 00:37:39.920
Reading, let's look at what
traditional knowledge might be.

00:37:39.920 --> 00:37:43.680
So, using that as a background
to talk about reading,

00:37:43.680 --> 00:37:45.000
what is traditional knowledge?

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:47.400
It's important to first
consider what is learning

00:37:47.400 --> 00:37:48.700
in Indian country.

00:37:48.700 --> 00:37:51.260
Traditional knowledge
created over time,

00:37:51.260 --> 00:37:53.310
passed down over generations,

00:37:53.310 --> 00:37:57.960
developed by the community via
living, evolving and growing.

00:37:57.960 --> 00:38:00.670
So that within tribal
communities,

00:38:00.670 --> 00:38:02.470
learning involves a lifetime

00:38:02.470 --> 00:38:05.510
of acquiring knowledge
of indigenous ways.

00:38:05.510 --> 00:38:08.460
Indigenous ways are the
traditional life ways

00:38:08.460 --> 00:38:12.390
of the original peoples also
called world view and approach

00:38:12.390 --> 00:38:16.230
to conducting everyday life,
interaction with others

00:38:16.230 --> 00:38:19.290
and philosophical or
religious perspectives.

00:38:19.290 --> 00:38:21.800
The heart of efforts
to support learning

00:38:21.800 --> 00:38:24.690
and reading is the
complete intersection

00:38:24.690 --> 00:38:28.530
between cultural protocols
of indigenous peoples

00:38:28.530 --> 00:38:32.030
and professional values
in holding, collecting,

00:38:32.030 --> 00:38:36.170
providing access and
using indigenous material

00:38:36.170 --> 00:38:38.410
in intellectual content.

00:38:38.410 --> 00:38:41.650
Work with tribal nations
should be entered respectfully

00:38:41.650 --> 00:38:44.770
and in ways that support
indigenous world view.

00:38:44.770 --> 00:38:49.450
And we might ask question such
as with their focus on English

00:38:49.450 --> 00:38:53.820
in the printed word, art
libraries, archives and museums

00:38:53.820 --> 00:38:56.650
as institution seen
by tribal communities

00:38:56.650 --> 00:38:59.490
as agents of colonization.

00:38:59.490 --> 00:39:03.060
Is literacy an active
decolonization?

00:39:03.060 --> 00:39:07.110
The process of removal of the
results of the colonization

00:39:07.110 --> 00:39:11.140
and the return of control to
indigenous peoples can support

00:39:11.140 --> 00:39:14.700
for reading, take steps
to rectify any adherence

00:39:14.700 --> 00:39:17.540
to colonial practices
and attitudes.

00:39:17.540 --> 00:39:22.270
And thus reading material
perpetuate harmful stereotypes

00:39:22.270 --> 00:39:23.880
to libraries, for example,

00:39:23.880 --> 00:39:27.610
represent formal educational
institutions similar

00:39:27.610 --> 00:39:31.490
to boarding schools that
restricted as acceptable forms

00:39:31.490 --> 00:39:34.590
of knowledge and
depressed native language

00:39:34.590 --> 00:39:37.370
and other cultural expressions?

00:39:37.370 --> 00:39:41.220
Note though that in the 10 years
or running a service initiative

00:39:41.220 --> 00:39:44.550
with my students, if I can
read, I can do anything,

00:39:44.550 --> 00:39:46.940
I never heard a native
parent ask me

00:39:46.940 --> 00:39:50.250
to not bring English language
books to their children schools.

00:39:50.250 --> 00:39:52.640
We delivered 100,000 new books

00:39:52.640 --> 00:39:56.160
over the 10 years
we ran the project.

00:39:56.160 --> 00:39:59.330
What do we know about
reading and ending country?

00:40:00.640 --> 00:40:04.520
In 1919, there was a study
by the US National Commission

00:40:04.520 --> 00:40:06.730
on Libraries and
Information Science

00:40:06.730 --> 00:40:10.620
and they found significant
barriers and limited access

00:40:10.620 --> 00:40:13.820
to library services by
American-Indians due to both

00:40:13.820 --> 00:40:15.840
to cultural differences and lack

00:40:15.840 --> 00:40:18.450
of culturally appropriate
resources.

00:40:18.450 --> 00:40:20.320
In 2007, just last year,

00:40:20.320 --> 00:40:24.230
Dr. Anthony Chow
conducted an evaluation

00:40:24.230 --> 00:40:27.930
for the Montana State
Library in their LSTA Program.

00:40:27.930 --> 00:40:31.650
And he found that barriers
to library services

00:40:31.650 --> 00:40:33.910
for tribal members still exist.

00:40:33.910 --> 00:40:36.350
There was little to
know convenient access

00:40:36.350 --> 00:40:39.970
to either a public or
tribal college library.

00:40:39.970 --> 00:40:42.970
There was little support and
awareness of libraries across--

00:40:42.970 --> 00:40:45.880
among tribal members because
their services were not

00:40:45.880 --> 00:40:49.250
typically a feature of
their indigenous world view.

00:40:49.250 --> 00:40:52.250
No work with tribal
communities, the challenges

00:40:52.250 --> 00:40:54.870
to engage adolescent,
children and youth older

00:40:54.870 --> 00:40:57.720
within elementary school age.

00:40:57.720 --> 00:41:00.550
Chow also found that
racial tension experienced

00:41:00.550 --> 00:41:03.150
by tribal members
visiting public libraries

00:41:03.150 --> 00:41:06.230
in bordering tribal
territory and the lack

00:41:06.230 --> 00:41:09.290
of financial resources for
tribal college librarians

00:41:09.290 --> 00:41:13.670
to prioritize early
literacy programing.

00:41:13.670 --> 00:41:16.210
What's happening in Indian
country, there are hundreds

00:41:16.210 --> 00:41:19.520
of tribal libraries and
archives, they exist in villages

00:41:19.520 --> 00:41:23.890
in Alaska, pueblos in New Mexico
and the Everglades, in Florida,

00:41:23.890 --> 00:41:27.280
in the Woodlands of Wisconsin,
Minnesota and Michigan.

00:41:27.280 --> 00:41:30.880
Reading takes place and is
supported amidst the challenges.

00:41:30.880 --> 00:41:33.970
These include tribal community
libraries that might serve

00:41:33.970 --> 00:41:38.280
as the public library, school
library, archive records,

00:41:38.280 --> 00:41:40.230
museum and language center.

00:41:40.230 --> 00:41:42.960
Tribal college libraries are
often the public libraries

00:41:42.960 --> 00:41:45.290
of their communities as well.

00:41:45.290 --> 00:41:48.330
And they are reading
advocates and champions.

00:41:48.330 --> 00:41:51.300
Tribal college librarians
gather to share their stories

00:41:51.300 --> 00:41:54.790
for one week, each year
in Bozeman, Montana.

00:41:54.790 --> 00:41:58.150
American-Indian Library
Association Members advocate

00:41:58.150 --> 00:42:01.070
and meet during the American
Library Association midwinter

00:42:01.070 --> 00:42:03.430
meeting and the annual
conference.

00:42:03.430 --> 00:42:05.640
And every two years,
a number is drawn

00:42:05.640 --> 00:42:09.060
to the International
Indigenous Librarians' Forum,

00:42:09.060 --> 00:42:13.660
which we'll note as 20th
anniversary in February 2019

00:42:13.660 --> 00:42:16.750
in Auckland [inaudible]
in New Zealand.

00:42:16.750 --> 00:42:19.520
We see new support for
reading through the recipients

00:42:19.520 --> 00:42:23.050
of funding through the Institute
of Museum and Library Services.

00:42:23.050 --> 00:42:26.470
Tribal libraries may receive
basic grants and may compete

00:42:26.470 --> 00:42:29.640
for enhancement grants and
deadlines are available

00:42:29.640 --> 00:42:32.340
at the imls.gov website.

00:42:32.340 --> 00:42:33.870
A few weeks ago, we had learned

00:42:33.870 --> 00:42:37.610
that the IMLS will be funding a
one-year planning grant called

00:42:37.610 --> 00:42:41.460
Reading Nation, that will
support the following efforts,

00:42:41.460 --> 00:42:44.930
the Blackfeet Tribal College
Library in collaboration

00:42:44.930 --> 00:42:48.100
with the University of North
Carolina at Greensboro,

00:42:48.100 --> 00:42:49.400
Department of Library

00:42:49.400 --> 00:42:51.760
and Information Studies
will do a number of things.

00:42:51.760 --> 00:42:53.970
They're going to establish
an advisory committee

00:42:53.970 --> 00:42:59.040
to help design a study of how
children, youth and families

00:42:59.040 --> 00:43:03.550
of the Blackfeet Nation
currently use library services.

00:43:03.550 --> 00:43:05.570
They're going to work with
that Advisory Committee

00:43:05.570 --> 00:43:09.720
to conduct an environmental scan
to understand the current state

00:43:09.720 --> 00:43:13.210
and potential factors
impacting tribal member use

00:43:13.210 --> 00:43:14.910
of library services.

00:43:14.910 --> 00:43:19.740
And then design a pilot test,
a community assessment process

00:43:19.740 --> 00:43:22.010
that identifies the
needs and challenges

00:43:22.010 --> 00:43:25.190
that tribal members
face in using public

00:43:25.190 --> 00:43:28.550
and community college
libraries with a specific focus

00:43:28.550 --> 00:43:31.390
on children and use services.

00:43:31.390 --> 00:43:34.850
Our data collection
starts in early July

00:43:34.850 --> 00:43:38.380
when the team including Dr.
Anthony Chow from the University

00:43:38.380 --> 00:43:40.790
of North Carolina at Greensboro.

00:43:40.790 --> 00:43:44.920
Ms. Aaron LaFromboise, Blackfeet
Community College tribal

00:43:44.920 --> 00:43:48.870
librarian and Blackfeet tribal
member and myself will meet

00:43:48.870 --> 00:43:51.560
in Browning, Montana
during the annual powwow.

00:43:51.560 --> 00:43:54.290
We will address this
research question,

00:43:54.290 --> 00:43:56.420
how might libraries collaborate

00:43:56.420 --> 00:43:59.230
in creating a reading
supportive environment

00:43:59.230 --> 00:44:02.660
for Blackfeet children,
youth and their caregivers?

00:44:02.660 --> 00:44:06.790
What is the current state

00:44:06.790 --> 00:44:10.010
of library services among
Blackfeet Tribal Members both on

00:44:10.010 --> 00:44:11.830
and off the reservation?

00:44:11.830 --> 00:44:14.310
What are the unique needs
and barriers to access

00:44:14.310 --> 00:44:17.890
to library services for tribal
members with an emphasis again

00:44:17.890 --> 00:44:19.580
on children, youth and families?

00:44:19.580 --> 00:44:22.100
And what are the
potential challenges faced

00:44:22.100 --> 00:44:24.670
by public libraries
in understanding

00:44:24.670 --> 00:44:26.330
and meeting those needs

00:44:26.330 --> 00:44:29.400
in culturally sensitive
and appropriate ways?

00:44:29.400 --> 00:44:31.280
We're following a
mix method approach

00:44:31.280 --> 00:44:33.840
of qualitative interviews,
focused group,

00:44:33.840 --> 00:44:38.790
surveys disseminated by print,
smartphone text and online.

00:44:38.790 --> 00:44:42.400
Participants were recruited
using convenience sampling,

00:44:42.400 --> 00:44:44.520
collecting data at
the annual powwow,

00:44:44.520 --> 00:44:46.630
stratified in purposeful
sampling

00:44:46.630 --> 00:44:49.420
and sharing a diverse
stratum of tribal members

00:44:49.420 --> 00:44:51.950
and public librarians
and a random sample

00:44:51.950 --> 00:44:55.540
of a 100 tribal members living
on or off the reservation.

00:44:55.540 --> 00:44:57.350
And we're currently
preparing to communicate

00:44:57.350 --> 00:44:58.650
with our Advisory Board

00:44:58.650 --> 00:45:01.420
in drafting the data
collection instruments.

00:45:01.420 --> 00:45:03.730
We'll have more to
share in a year.

00:45:03.730 --> 00:45:06.420
I'm going to close with
introducing just a couple

00:45:06.420 --> 00:45:10.270
of cases that illustrate the
impact of writing and reading

00:45:10.270 --> 00:45:13.880
and including and not including
in some cases native people.

00:45:13.880 --> 00:45:15.770
And there aren't
answers to these cases.

00:45:15.770 --> 00:45:18.750
I teach a class for the
University of Texas at Austin

00:45:18.750 --> 00:45:22.540
and for the University of Hawaii
at Manoa on access and care

00:45:22.540 --> 00:45:25.650
of traditional cultural
knowledge and we use this

00:45:25.650 --> 00:45:29.090
as real examples of things
that actually I experienced.

00:45:29.090 --> 00:45:31.290
So, imagine you're
adding author's reception

00:45:31.290 --> 00:45:35.610
at a conference and you're
asked by nonnative writer

00:45:35.610 --> 00:45:38.780
about your endorsement of
their latest children's book.

00:45:38.780 --> 00:45:42.340
And the writer ask, tells you
that she went to the reservation

00:45:42.340 --> 00:45:44.370
where the book is based
and could not find anyone

00:45:44.370 --> 00:45:46.420
who could write the
book as well as she did

00:45:46.420 --> 00:45:49.120
and how might you
respond to that question

00:45:49.120 --> 00:45:53.500
and which I avoided for
three times around the room.

00:45:53.500 --> 00:45:56.540
And then had to face
the author and describe

00:45:56.540 --> 00:45:58.740
at least what I thought
of that book.

00:45:58.740 --> 00:46:01.530
And you can-- I finally
had to say you're not going

00:46:01.530 --> 00:46:03.100
to get a good review
and then that.

00:46:03.100 --> 00:46:05.580
So that kind of closed
that conversation.

00:46:05.580 --> 00:46:07.750
Let's say your professional
organization is creating a

00:46:07.750 --> 00:46:10.530
product as a promotional
calendar, and each month

00:46:10.530 --> 00:46:11.890
of the calendar is
going to feature.

00:46:11.890 --> 00:46:14.680
And you hope a native
writer and your approach

00:46:14.680 --> 00:46:17.010
because you're the
president of that association,

00:46:17.010 --> 00:46:18.320
and you will be president.

00:46:18.320 --> 00:46:20.390
And your approach is saying
this would be a wonderful thing

00:46:20.390 --> 00:46:23.100
for you to advocate during
your year and is going to--

00:46:23.100 --> 00:46:24.400
and I said that's great.

00:46:24.400 --> 00:46:25.880
Oh, the president--
whoever is asked.

00:46:25.880 --> 00:46:27.230
That's great.

00:46:27.230 --> 00:46:29.940
And because each page
will feature an author

00:46:29.940 --> 00:46:33.900
that you're nominating, a native
writer, a native illustrator.

00:46:33.900 --> 00:46:36.710
And months later you get a call
saying, well, they've decided--

00:46:36.710 --> 00:46:39.640
the committee decided to go with
Paul Goble whom you remember

00:46:39.640 --> 00:46:41.690
as someone who did
received the Caldecott Award

00:46:41.690 --> 00:46:46.130
but who wasn't native and
borrowed stories from a tribe.

00:46:46.130 --> 00:46:48.050
And you say that's
really too bad

00:46:48.050 --> 00:46:50.420
because you can't endorse
the product anymore.

00:46:50.420 --> 00:46:51.800
And the product is featured

00:46:51.800 --> 00:46:55.700
on your association's graphics
catalogue two months later

00:46:55.700 --> 00:46:58.560
in the American Indian
Library Association, find out.

00:46:58.560 --> 00:47:01.320
And then the rest becomes
a story that's published

00:47:01.320 --> 00:47:02.620
in a handbook.

00:47:02.620 --> 00:47:05.410
So, read what happens next.

00:47:05.410 --> 00:47:07.760
A friend of yours wants to
write a children's book,

00:47:07.760 --> 00:47:10.730
former student and is located
a story from your tribe

00:47:10.730 --> 00:47:13.910
in an old anthropological report
and tells you this is going

00:47:13.910 --> 00:47:17.010
to be a great honoring
experience for her.

00:47:17.010 --> 00:47:20.660
And I asked who is going
to see the process?

00:47:20.660 --> 00:47:22.990
And that ends that
conversation as well.

00:47:22.990 --> 00:47:27.110
And then a friend describes
visiting a reservation

00:47:27.110 --> 00:47:29.470
in Northern Minnesota
where you have a connection

00:47:29.470 --> 00:47:32.870
and it's everything that they
expected to see, old cards,

00:47:32.870 --> 00:47:35.030
lots of dude, and lots of dogs.

00:47:35.030 --> 00:47:37.440
So, these are the source
of things that you face

00:47:37.440 --> 00:47:40.060
and hear about, and
they are contemporary.

00:47:40.060 --> 00:47:43.430
They happen within our lifetime
and perhaps just last year.

00:47:43.430 --> 00:47:46.690
And they illustrate not only
what you need to support,

00:47:46.690 --> 00:47:51.210
just general world view of
nonnative and native people,

00:47:51.210 --> 00:47:54.520
but the sorts of barriers and
challenges and opportunities

00:47:54.520 --> 00:47:56.880
that people have who
worked with native people

00:47:56.880 --> 00:47:58.250
and with native children.

