because we've just hashed this

01:07:19.170 --> 01:07:23.050
out and there's always a tension
between how we translate this

01:07:23.050 --> 01:07:25.060
from French to English.

01:07:25.060 --> 01:07:28.160
So any advice you have is great.

01:07:28.160 --> 01:07:30.670
We believe that information
and education empower people

01:07:30.670 --> 01:07:31.970
and give them the ability

01:07:31.970 --> 01:07:34.240
to make enlightened choices
for a better feature.

01:07:34.240 --> 01:07:35.750
To achieve that goal,
we built bridges

01:07:35.750 --> 01:07:39.500
between the information
society which is us and those

01:07:39.500 --> 01:07:42.800
who are excluded from it.

01:07:42.800 --> 01:07:49.070
And our scope of intervention
since 2007 has been classified,

01:07:49.070 --> 01:07:50.590
I think, in three pillars.

01:07:50.590 --> 01:07:53.620
We've been really thinking
about humanitarian contexts,

01:07:53.620 --> 01:07:55.930
places where-- that have
suffered from natural

01:07:55.930 --> 01:07:57.790
or political disasters.

01:07:57.790 --> 01:08:01.540
We've been focusing on
education and literacy

01:08:01.540 --> 01:08:04.990
and also using our
library spaces

01:08:04.990 --> 01:08:06.880
for entrepreneurship programs.

01:08:06.880 --> 01:08:13.180
So the last time I had an
opportunity to speak here,

01:08:13.180 --> 01:08:17.870
we were really in the sort of
focusing on our flagship program

01:08:17.870 --> 01:08:19.890
which is called the Ideas Box.

01:08:19.890 --> 01:08:23.220
And this is something that
we built learning from work

01:08:23.220 --> 01:08:25.770
that we had done in Haiti
after the earthquake.

01:08:25.770 --> 01:08:28.520
One of the biggest challenges
that we had was really

01:08:28.520 --> 01:08:30.400
in the supply chain, all right,

01:08:30.400 --> 01:08:32.400
books getting wet
during transportation,

01:08:32.400 --> 01:08:35.630
not having storage or security
when it arrives to a place

01:08:35.630 --> 01:08:38.170
that is just suffered
from a natural disaster

01:08:38.170 --> 01:08:41.550
or to a refugee camp in
the African great lakes.

01:08:41.550 --> 01:08:43.320
So we built this with support

01:08:43.320 --> 01:08:45.650
from Philippe Starck's
design team,

01:08:45.650 --> 01:08:50.400
something that could be easily
deployed in these contexts,

01:08:50.400 --> 01:08:52.180
something that could be fit

01:08:52.180 --> 01:08:54.550
on to standard transportation
pallets waterproof during

01:08:54.550 --> 01:09:01.270
transportation unfolds
into these modules

01:09:01.270 --> 01:09:05.720
that eventually becomes
a full size media center.

01:09:05.720 --> 01:09:12.120
With the support from the
international literacy award,

01:09:12.120 --> 01:09:17.970
we've been able to grow this
out now to, we've gotten now

01:09:17.970 --> 01:09:21.160
over a hundred around in
the world and reaching

01:09:21.160 --> 01:09:26.720
over a million people and with
over 2,800 different kinds

01:09:26.720 --> 01:09:31.850
of curated content that we
customized for each context,

01:09:31.850 --> 01:09:35.240
the sort of flagship
program has been in Burundi

01:09:35.240 --> 01:09:38.100
and refugee camps where
partnered with UNHCR.

01:09:38.100 --> 01:09:40.190
But we've also done programs,

01:09:40.190 --> 01:09:44.210
last year our largest
program was in Columbia,

01:09:44.210 --> 01:09:46.740
it's part of the peace building
initiatives with the ministry

01:09:46.740 --> 01:09:50.170
of culture and the
national library.

01:09:50.170 --> 01:09:55.880
And coming up we'll be having a
few ideas boxes in Puerto Rico

01:09:55.880 --> 01:10:00.240
as part of the disaster
relief efforts there thinking

01:10:00.240 --> 01:10:04.300
