And this will be
more of a story.

01:10:47.300 --> 01:10:55.560
So in 2015, we had the Ideas Box
in New York in the South Bronx

01:10:55.560 --> 01:10:57.960
where we were working with
the New York Public Library

01:10:57.960 --> 01:11:01.250
to create pop up
libraries around the city.

01:11:01.250 --> 01:11:04.750
And we had an ethnographer
from NYU follow us

01:11:04.750 --> 01:11:09.480
for six months thinking
through and trying

01:11:09.480 --> 01:11:12.560
to explore what are some of the
challenges that families have

01:11:12.560 --> 01:11:16.030
with accessing library programs.

01:11:16.030 --> 01:11:19.290
So we setup the Ideas
Box in public parks,

01:11:19.290 --> 01:11:22.890
lobbies of low income housing,
legal aid waiting offices,

01:11:22.890 --> 01:11:28.550
hospitals, barbershops, street
corner, subway stations.

01:11:28.550 --> 01:11:30.280
And one of the things
that we were finding

01:11:30.280 --> 01:11:32.250
when we were interviewing
families was

01:11:32.250 --> 01:11:34.680
that there's a very
big difference

01:11:34.680 --> 01:11:38.760
between the availability
of programs and resources

01:11:38.760 --> 01:11:41.020
and the accessibility
of those programs.

01:11:41.020 --> 01:11:42.810
And one of the, one
of the main barriers

01:11:42.810 --> 01:11:44.940
that we found was really
a scheduling barrier

01:11:44.940 --> 01:11:46.980
in terms of participation.

01:11:46.980 --> 01:11:50.780
Offering a literacy program

01:11:50.780 --> 01:11:54.340
that meets 6 p.m. every
Tuesday is really, really tough

01:11:54.340 --> 01:11:58.080
for families that rely on
service industry jobs, right.

01:11:58.080 --> 01:11:59.890
You can't afford to miss
a shift, you miss one

01:11:59.890 --> 01:12:02.120
of the classes, you're
embarrassed to go back,

01:12:02.120 --> 01:12:05.280
one of the main reasons why a
lot of the families we talked

01:12:05.280 --> 01:12:08.600
to were not able to bring
their kids or for themselves

01:12:08.600 --> 01:12:12.360
to participate in, not only
library programs but a lot

01:12:12.360 --> 01:12:14.890
of literacy opportunities.

01:12:14.890 --> 01:12:19.240
But this raises a huge
challenge, right, because those,

01:12:19.240 --> 01:12:22.770
of course, are going to be
the most tested, you're going

01:12:22.770 --> 01:12:26.740
to have much more evaluation
opportunity at a physical site

01:12:26.740 --> 01:12:28.480
than if you're out
in the community.

01:12:28.480 --> 01:12:33.780
And also it's much
harder to design, right,

01:12:33.780 --> 01:12:36.080
if you don't know how many
people are going to show up,

01:12:36.080 --> 01:12:37.650
you don't know what
ages they are,

01:12:37.650 --> 01:12:41.410
you don't know what their
reading level is going to be.

01:12:41.410 --> 01:12:43.010
And so, we've been
exploring this now

01:12:43.010 --> 01:12:46.700
for the last three years really
trying to kind of think through,

01:12:46.700 --> 01:12:51.380
how do we work with our library
partners to think about outreach

01:12:51.380 --> 01:12:53.750
and I use that word
acknowledging

01:12:53.750 --> 01:12:56.860
that it can be defined in
so many different ways.

01:12:56.860 --> 01:13:01.270
We had-- One of our library
partners said, you know,

01:13:01.270 --> 01:13:04.990
outreach is meaning less in
some ways because so much

01:13:04.990 --> 01:13:06.620
of the work we have to do is--

01:13:06.620 --> 01:13:10.000
has to be embedded in the
community to begin with, right?

01:13:10.000 --> 01:13:14.620
What we found was
that one of the best,

01:13:14.620 --> 01:13:20.720
best places to do this
work was in laundromats.

01:13:20.720 --> 01:13:25.690
And so laundromats are
really interesting spaces

01:13:25.690 --> 01:13:31.120
because you have
to go every week

01:13:31.120 --> 01:13:34.080
if you don't have a washer dryer
at home, and you were there

01:13:34.080 --> 01:13:36.400
for 90 minutes on average.

01:13:36.400 --> 01:13:39.000
In the winter if it's--
if you're in a cold place,

01:13:39.000 --> 01:13:41.970
you're going more than
once a week especially

01:13:41.970 --> 01:13:44.010
if you have many kids.

01:13:44.010 --> 01:13:46.990
The more layers, the more
laundry you have to wash.

01:13:46.990 --> 01:13:50.370
And what's been interesting,
there's been no day

01:13:50.370 --> 01:13:51.670
of the last two years

01:13:51.670 --> 01:13:52.970
that I haven't said
the word laundromat.

01:13:52.970 --> 01:13:57.100
And so, I've been learning
a lot about the industry,

01:13:57.100 --> 01:14:02.140
it's a growing industry which
I think is really interesting

01:14:02.140 --> 01:14:06.550
for those of us who
aren't in that space.

01:14:06.550 --> 01:14:10.360
The revenues and profits of
laundromats has been going up,

01:14:10.360 --> 01:14:14.210
I think as a consequence
of rising poverty.

01:14:14.210 --> 01:14:17.520
What you see in this
basis is really, you know,

01:14:17.520 --> 01:14:19.400
sometimes if you run a
college campus, of course,

01:14:19.400 --> 01:14:22.750
you get college students but for
the most part you're really--

01:14:22.750 --> 01:14:26.170
the clients of the
laundromat are lowest income,

01:14:26.170 --> 01:14:29.640
can't save the capital $500 to
have a washer dryer at home,

01:14:29.640 --> 01:14:32.850
live in space that is too
small, right, or in a building

01:14:32.850 --> 01:14:35.750
that doesn't have
those amenities.

01:14:35.750 --> 01:14:40.350
And so, over the last year what
we've been doing is partnering

01:14:40.350 --> 01:14:45.360
with our local library branches
state county and city libraries

01:14:45.360 --> 01:14:51.270
as well as most excitingly a
trade group called the Coin

01:14:51.270 --> 01:14:54.500
Laundry Association
and they have

01:14:54.500 --> 01:14:59.650
over 30,000 small business
members across the country.

01:14:59.650 --> 01:15:02.850
And we're trying to turn now
all 30,000 of those member sites

01:15:02.850 --> 01:15:05.580
into extensions of
their local library.

01:15:05.580 --> 01:15:07.980
What I love about this is
that we're trying to think

01:15:07.980 --> 01:15:11.540
through how to build out these
public private partnerships

01:15:11.540 --> 01:15:13.740
at the really hyperlocal
level, right?

01:15:13.740 --> 01:15:15.980
Because when you really
think about it, I don't think

01:15:15.980 --> 01:15:21.760
that the innovation behind
this is a product, right?

01:15:21.760 --> 01:15:23.060
As we've been exploring this,

01:15:23.060 --> 01:15:25.080
we found that Chicago Public
Library has been doing

01:15:25.080 --> 01:15:29.240
laundromat programs
for the last 20 years.

01:15:29.240 --> 01:15:32.520
And so, we brought over
15 other organizations

01:15:32.520 --> 01:15:37.470
that have been doing this siloed
laundromat programs together

01:15:37.470 --> 01:15:40.890
to meet in Chicago with the
Coin Laundry Association,

01:15:40.890 --> 01:15:43.110
to build up the tools
and capacity building

01:15:43.110 --> 01:15:46.650
for any other organization that
wants to do this themselves.

01:15:46.650 --> 01:15:49.660
I think that the reason why we
want to focus on that rather

01:15:49.660 --> 01:15:51.100
than as Libraries
Without Borders,

01:15:51.100 --> 01:15:52.790
built at our own
laundromat sites

01:15:52.790 --> 01:15:56.600
and operate them is pretty
obvious to me, which is that,

01:15:56.600 --> 01:16:01.690
you know, I myself won't know
the contexts, what texts curate,

01:16:01.690 --> 01:16:03.390
what challenges people
are facing as well

01:16:03.390 --> 01:16:04.900
as our local partners.

01:16:04.900 --> 01:16:10.530
And what's dynamic about these
hyperlocal public-private

01:16:10.530 --> 01:16:14.250
partnerships between the small
business really Mom-and-Pop Shop

01:16:14.250 --> 01:16:16.570
and not even necessarily
a library system

01:16:16.570 --> 01:16:20.780
but a library branch is that
they can be super, super dynamic

01:16:20.780 --> 01:16:22.160
with changing needs, right?

01:16:22.160 --> 01:16:26.490
So when new questions come
up, you change the content.

01:16:26.490 --> 01:16:29.580
Last month a lot of the
library systems found

01:16:29.580 --> 01:16:32.490
that people were asking a
lot of the tax questions

01:16:32.490 --> 01:16:34.690
and so we're trying
to teach literacy

01:16:34.690 --> 01:16:39.280
through helping people sort
through those, those questions.

01:16:39.280 --> 01:16:41.580
A lot of that is local.

01:16:47.290 --> 01:16:52.050
When-- I spoke with one
parent, one mother in one

01:16:52.050 --> 01:16:55.260
of the laundromat sites
in Detroit that we have

01:16:55.260 --> 01:16:59.090
and this is getting to a more
macro level question that I have

01:16:59.090 --> 01:17:02.440
for this group which is, you
know, we've had this prompt

01:17:02.440 --> 01:17:07.070
of talking about what programs
work, what programs don't.

01:17:07.070 --> 01:17:10.540
How do we define success
in our case, right?

01:17:10.540 --> 01:17:15.350
Because literacy rates are
certainly one quantitative way

01:17:15.350 --> 01:17:16.870
to measure it but
I'd like to get

01:17:16.870 --> 01:17:21.370
at something that's little
bit more emotional and social

01:17:21.370 --> 01:17:22.750
and how do we define that.

01:17:22.750 --> 01:17:26.240
So when I was in Detroit,
spoke with one parent

01:17:26.240 --> 01:17:29.360
who is participating regularly

01:17:29.360 --> 01:17:32.730
in the laundromat
literacy programs.

01:17:32.730 --> 01:17:38.090
And she said, you know,
her story was she had--

01:17:38.090 --> 01:17:44.410
she was a single mom, had just
moved to Detroit, she had moved

01:17:44.410 --> 01:17:46.810
with her boyfriend at that time.

01:17:46.810 --> 01:17:48.110
He had left her.

01:17:48.110 --> 01:17:49.510
She didn't know anyone
else in Detroit.

01:17:49.510 --> 01:17:51.150
She'd been there now for a year.

01:17:51.150 --> 01:17:52.740
And this was-- she
said the first time

01:17:52.740 --> 01:17:56.330
that anyone had spoken to her
and ask her how she was doing?

01:17:56.330 --> 01:18:00.020
And it really stuck with
me because I think one

01:18:00.020 --> 01:18:04.260
of the main barriers that I
think a lot of people have

01:18:04.260 --> 01:18:12.750
with accessing existing
resources, right, is the social

01:18:12.750 --> 01:18:14.050
and emotional; barrier.

01:18:14.050 --> 01:18:16.490
If you don't have the social
networks that are opening you

01:18:16.490 --> 01:18:18.370
to these opportunities,
if you don't have--

01:18:18.370 --> 01:18:20.790
if you don't think that
that's basis for you,

01:18:20.790 --> 01:18:24.780
it doesn't matter how well
we design the program inside

01:18:24.780 --> 01:18:27.920
if people don't feel
like they can use it.

01:18:27.920 --> 01:18:32.330
And so, how can we-- as a
community focusing on literacy,

01:18:32.330 --> 01:18:34.770
think about not only
generating good content

01:18:34.770 --> 01:18:38.490
and making it available but also
think about how we can think

01:18:38.490 --> 01:18:44.550
about the softer elements to
make them actually accessible.

01:18:44.550 --> 01:18:51.040
One other finding that
we've had is thinking

01:18:51.040 --> 01:18:52.340
about how we curate content.

01:18:52.340 --> 01:18:54.290
And this gets back to
why I think this sort

01:18:54.290 --> 01:18:58.160
of hyper local public-private
partnership is really exciting.

01:18:58.160 --> 01:19:01.380
I think that there's
a big difference

01:19:01.380 --> 01:19:04.520
between comprehensive
information

01:19:04.520 --> 01:19:07.170
and relevant information.

01:19:07.170 --> 01:19:10.970
And so, in the laundromats
where we've been putting-- not--

01:19:10.970 --> 01:19:12.300
yes, not only a bookshelf

01:19:12.300 --> 01:19:15.240
but also what we've
been doing is putting--

01:19:15.240 --> 01:19:16.790
moving one of the
folding stations out,

01:19:16.790 --> 01:19:20.620
putting for laptops
or desktop computers

01:19:20.620 --> 01:19:22.560
with the curated Wi-Fi hotspot.

01:19:22.560 --> 01:19:28.300
I think there's a big difference
between providing open access

01:19:28.300 --> 01:19:30.370
to internet and curating
the space

01:19:30.370 --> 01:19:34.710
to be a really education
focused, literacy focused corner

01:19:34.710 --> 01:19:38.930
of the laundromat where
Wi-Fi is really curated

01:19:38.930 --> 01:19:44.140
around our content partners,
PBS KIDS, Too Small to Fail,

01:19:44.140 --> 01:19:46.660
really thinking about how
we curate that content

01:19:46.660 --> 01:19:49.520
so that it's timed between
wash and dry cycles.

01:19:49.520 --> 01:19:54.850
Thinking about how we can have
this generational conversation

01:19:54.850 --> 01:20:00.440
happening in that space

01:20:00.440 --> 01:20:03.840
and answering people's
most urgent questions.

01:20:03.840 --> 01:20:07.440
So what we've been
finding is instead

01:20:07.440 --> 01:20:11.020
of having this set curriculum
and this again gets to really,

01:20:11.020 --> 01:20:15.290
really tough challenge
on evaluation,

01:20:15.290 --> 01:20:18.040
instead of answering--
providing, you know,

01:20:18.040 --> 01:20:19.770
this is the curriculum
for the laundromat,

01:20:19.770 --> 01:20:22.970
what we've been doing is
convening local organizations

01:20:22.970 --> 01:20:26.580
to activate the laundromat
as a community anchor, right?

01:20:26.580 --> 01:20:30.730
A community center of sorts
during the laundromat's busiest

01:20:30.730 --> 01:20:32.640
hours and for those of
you that haven't been

01:20:32.640 --> 01:20:35.910
to a laundromat recently, some
of them can have 200 washers,

01:20:35.910 --> 01:20:38.180
200 dryers on the weekends.

01:20:38.180 --> 01:20:40.880
You have over 300
families at any given time

01:20:40.880 --> 01:20:42.200
that you can be working with.

01:20:42.200 --> 01:20:45.030
And so the demand is-- it's so
much greater than the supply

01:20:45.030 --> 01:20:47.580
when we bring our
librarians there.

01:20:47.580 --> 01:20:50.100
But thinking through, you know,

01:20:50.100 --> 01:20:53.230
people that we've been having
these conversations with

01:20:53.230 --> 01:20:55.760
and running this program with
have something very urgent

01:20:55.760 --> 01:20:57.930
that they need to that day.

01:20:57.930 --> 01:21:02.360
How can we make sure that the
literacy curriculum especially--

01:21:02.360 --> 01:21:03.880
and the digital literacy
curriculum

01:21:03.880 --> 01:21:08.030
that we're providing is taught
experientially to answer

01:21:08.030 --> 01:21:11.500
that question, right, how do
you not just to use literacy

01:21:11.500 --> 01:21:15.630
to read a fiction book
but how do you use it

01:21:15.630 --> 01:21:18.850
to find health information,
sign up for health insurance,

01:21:18.850 --> 01:21:23.600
figure out how to do your taxes
and learn all those other skills

01:21:23.600 --> 01:21:26.410
which I think literacy is the
only way you open the door

01:21:26.410 --> 01:21:29.130
to those opportunities for.

01:21:29.130 --> 01:21:30.980
And so, I would like
to end on a couple,

01:21:30.980 --> 01:21:32.790
just final closing
thoughts which, you know,

01:21:32.790 --> 01:21:36.740
again it's not rocket science,
this have been tried and tested

01:21:36.740 --> 01:21:39.260
and explained by others but what
we're finding as we're trying

01:21:39.260 --> 01:21:41.420
to work on this piece
of the supply chain

01:21:41.420 --> 01:21:45.930
of knowledge is really
been on our mind is

01:21:45.930 --> 01:21:48.730
that the availability
of programs

01:21:48.730 --> 01:21:52.780
and content does not necessarily
mean that it's accessible

01:21:52.780 --> 01:21:58.020
and that comprehensive libraries
are not necessarily relevant.

01:21:58.020 --> 01:21:59.820
Thank you.

01:21:59.820 --> 01:22:07.040
[ Applause ]

