&gt;&gt; Rachel Walker:
Yeah, I represent a lot

01:22:52.800 --> 01:22:55.240
of different folks, which
has been exciting for me

01:22:55.240 --> 01:22:58.520
over the 30 years in my
career in children's literacy.

01:22:58.520 --> 01:23:01.850
I'm here today really
representing Reading Rockets,

01:23:01.850 --> 01:23:05.480
which is a national
project of WETA,

01:23:05.480 --> 01:23:07.910
the flagship public
television station here

01:23:07.910 --> 01:23:11.960
in our nation's capital which
you may know for PBS news hour,

01:23:11.960 --> 01:23:18.090
Ken Burns documentaries but
WETA really about 15 years ago,

01:23:18.090 --> 01:23:21.940
I had this idea that it would
be a good idea to take advantage

01:23:21.940 --> 01:23:26.900
of this internet thing and to
use that to disseminate some

01:23:26.900 --> 01:23:30.510
of the best reading research
that's out there because we know

01:23:30.510 --> 01:23:34.350
that educators and parents
want that information.

01:23:34.350 --> 01:23:36.690
And so, we started
with, you know,

01:23:36.690 --> 01:23:39.130
what the National
Institute of Child Health

01:23:39.130 --> 01:23:41.630
and Human Development and the
National Reading Panel were

01:23:41.630 --> 01:23:45.040
working on to really
determine what is the best

01:23:45.040 --> 01:23:46.460
in teaching reading.

01:23:46.460 --> 01:23:49.930
And we took that information
and what we know best

01:23:49.930 --> 01:23:52.450
which is the power
of story telling

01:23:52.450 --> 01:23:55.750
through public television and
turn it into something to try

01:23:55.750 --> 01:23:58.770
to really demystify
the reading research

01:23:58.770 --> 01:24:01.950
because that's really important.

01:24:01.950 --> 01:24:06.860
Teaching reading is complex
and it needs to be responsive

01:24:06.860 --> 01:24:14.130
to the needs of each child so
we're not doing the PowerPoint.

01:24:21.720 --> 01:24:25.330
No? That's all right.

01:24:25.330 --> 01:24:27.630
I can talk without pictures.

01:24:37.780 --> 01:24:47.140
No? OK. So what I wanted to
say in terms of why I feel

01:24:47.140 --> 01:24:49.920
like Reading Rockets is such
an important reading promotion

01:24:49.920 --> 01:24:54.510
partner in the literacy
community is that we need

01:24:54.510 --> 01:24:57.570
to remember that we've
got to speak to that,

01:24:57.570 --> 01:25:01.340
that reading instruction
is important.

01:25:01.340 --> 01:25:05.230
High quality reading instruction
break down those barriers

01:25:05.230 --> 01:25:09.100
so that you are ready
to read, to learn.

01:25:09.100 --> 01:25:11.130
Sometimes I feel like
that's kind of obvious

01:25:11.130 --> 01:25:15.270
that it doesn't get mentioned
but we really do need

01:25:15.270 --> 01:25:18.480
to remember that we have kids

01:25:18.480 --> 01:25:20.370
who aren't going
to love reading.

01:25:20.370 --> 01:25:22.870
And one of the reasons that
they might not love reading

01:25:22.870 --> 01:25:24.210
or might avoid reading is

01:25:24.210 --> 01:25:26.380
because they haven't
mastered it,

01:25:26.380 --> 01:25:29.600
they haven't mastered
decoding to become fluent,

01:25:29.600 --> 01:25:32.720
they haven't gotten interested
in learning new words or looking

01:25:32.720 --> 01:25:35.450
at new ideas and they're
really frustrated.

01:25:35.450 --> 01:25:39.800
So reading promotion helps kind
of create those entry points

01:25:39.800 --> 01:25:43.620
for those kids who are learning
or those kids who are striving.

01:25:43.620 --> 01:25:47.020
We have to look at
ability and inclination.

01:25:47.020 --> 01:25:50.110
So one of the projects
that I've been involved

01:25:50.110 --> 01:25:52.850
in through Reading
Rockets but also just

01:25:52.850 --> 01:25:56.720
because I'm really interested in
reading and getting kids excited

01:25:56.720 --> 01:26:00.670
about reading was when
I was actually working

01:26:00.670 --> 01:26:03.800
with Ms. Lynda Johnson Robb,
Reading is Fundamental.

01:26:03.800 --> 01:26:07.930
I started partnering with the
National Education Association

01:26:07.930 --> 01:26:10.310
when they launched to
Read Across America.

01:26:10.310 --> 01:26:13.160
Who knows what Read
Across America is?

01:26:13.160 --> 01:26:15.790
Yes. Who knows who wrote,
"You're never too old,

01:26:15.790 --> 01:26:19.890
too wacky, too wild, to pick up
a book and read with a child"?

01:26:19.890 --> 01:26:21.520
Who-- so say it, who wrote it?

01:26:21.520 --> 01:26:22.830
&gt;&gt; [Simultaneously] Dr. Seuss.

01:26:22.830 --> 01:26:25.370
&gt;&gt; Rachel Walker: Dr.
Seuss did not write that.

01:26:25.370 --> 01:26:29.050
I'm so sorry to tell you
that, that was written

01:26:29.050 --> 01:26:33.470
by an NEA staff person
and you can see it all

01:26:33.470 --> 01:26:37.990
over the internet credited to
Dr. Seuss but no that belongs

01:26:37.990 --> 01:26:42.870
to Anita Merina who
authored that little rhyme.

01:26:42.870 --> 01:26:47.380
And it was the rhyme that
any-- I was attracted to,

01:26:47.380 --> 01:26:50.910
by Dr. Seuss and, of
course ,the hat, you know,

01:26:50.910 --> 01:26:54.370
as Benita was saying with the
Get Caught Reading campaign.

01:26:54.370 --> 01:26:58.390
It's that oddness, that
juxtaposition of, you know,

01:26:58.390 --> 01:27:01.500
a Supreme Court Justice wearing
a cat in a hat hat is going

01:27:01.500 --> 01:27:03.820
to get your attention
and makes you think,

01:27:03.820 --> 01:27:07.540
oh maybe this is something that
I should be paying attention to.

01:27:07.540 --> 01:27:11.420
But NEA really felt like Dr.
Seuss epitomized, you know,

01:27:11.420 --> 01:27:13.790
a love of children
and a love of learning

01:27:13.790 --> 01:27:19.410
and this fun fantastical
rhyme and looking in the,

01:27:19.410 --> 01:27:22.010
the book that we have the
report from Scholastic.

01:27:22.010 --> 01:27:25.530
You see, Dr. Seuss
is all over that.

01:27:25.530 --> 01:27:27.990
So he's dear to many folks.

01:27:27.990 --> 01:27:31.020
And that's great
and it really has--

01:27:31.020 --> 01:27:35.830
for 20 years Read Across America
has generated participation

01:27:35.830 --> 01:27:38.820
annually from about
45 million adults

01:27:38.820 --> 01:27:43.930
and kids reading together, which
is tremendous, it's on the map.

01:27:43.930 --> 01:27:47.220
So that's great,
that's been working.

01:27:47.220 --> 01:27:49.710
We've gotten kids
excited about reading and

01:27:49.710 --> 01:27:54.550
yet it was time to change.

01:27:54.550 --> 01:27:59.260
NEA really recognized
that change was needed.

01:27:59.260 --> 01:28:02.620
It was the hat that was starting
to get all the attention.

01:28:02.620 --> 01:28:06.530
It wasn't what kids needed
or what adults wanted to do

01:28:06.530 --> 01:28:08.580
in their interactions with kids.

01:28:08.580 --> 01:28:13.480
So, NEA really took the
opportunity to say we need

01:28:13.480 --> 01:28:16.560
to do more, we need to do more
than a one day celebration

01:28:16.560 --> 01:28:18.440
on Dr. Seuss's birthday.

01:28:18.440 --> 01:28:21.820
We need to launch readers
year round and we need

01:28:21.820 --> 01:28:28.030
to give them access to both
those windows and mirrors

01:28:28.030 --> 01:28:31.280
and have for the past
several years really place

01:28:31.280 --> 01:28:34.100
to greater emphasis
on year round literacy

01:28:34.100 --> 01:28:38.330
with an annual calendar and
annual resources that focus

01:28:38.330 --> 01:28:40.560
on building a nation
of diverse readers.

01:28:40.560 --> 01:28:45.250
So looking at books
by Native Americans,

01:28:45.250 --> 01:28:50.430
by folks from all walks of life
to kind of get the story out

01:28:50.430 --> 01:28:52.010
and hopefully what that's going

01:28:52.010 --> 01:28:54.340
to do is encourage
more diversity,

01:28:54.340 --> 01:28:56.720
encourage more diversity
in publishing

01:28:56.720 --> 01:29:00.480
and encourage more
diversity in kids reading.

01:29:00.480 --> 01:29:04.080
The other hat that I've
been wearing lately is

01:29:04.080 --> 01:29:06.470
as a program director
for a nonprofit here

01:29:06.470 --> 01:29:09.080
in DC called Everybody Wins.

01:29:09.080 --> 01:29:15.120
And Everybody Wins was started
about 25 years ago here in DC

01:29:15.120 --> 01:29:20.040
by folks, right over here on
Capitol Hill, Senator Kennedy,

01:29:20.040 --> 01:29:22.880
Senator Jeffords realized
that right in the shadow

01:29:22.880 --> 01:29:26.850
of the capitol, folks
were not learning to read,

01:29:26.850 --> 01:29:29.500
kids were not being read
to, they didn't have access

01:29:29.500 --> 01:29:34.420
to books, their school library
was blocked, so they decided one

01:29:34.420 --> 01:29:36.640
of the things that
they could do was go

01:29:36.640 --> 01:29:39.500
over during their lunch
hour and read to kids.

01:29:39.500 --> 01:29:45.380
And we found that that worked
that having a kid and a book

01:29:45.380 --> 01:29:47.040
and an adult and a book share

01:29:47.040 --> 01:29:51.330
and spend time together
actually made a difference.

01:29:51.330 --> 01:29:55.390
Everybody Wins in DC now
serves about a thousand kids

01:29:55.390 --> 01:29:59.690
with readers from all over the
city, from all walks of life

01:29:59.690 --> 01:30:02.620
and we make sure that
kids are taking books home

01:30:02.620 --> 01:30:05.590
so that we're improving their
access to books at home.

01:30:05.590 --> 01:30:10.150
But what's really key are those
shared reading experiences

01:30:10.150 --> 01:30:15.970
and they're building connections
that are lasting a lifetime.

01:30:15.970 --> 01:30:21.000
I recently met a young
man who called to say,

01:30:21.000 --> 01:30:24.500
that 20 years ago he
had been a student

01:30:24.500 --> 01:30:28.440
at Thompson Elementary
School in DC and he wanted

01:30:28.440 --> 01:30:32.850
to know how could he now
become a reading mentor

01:30:32.850 --> 01:30:36.870
because his reading mentor
had meant so much to him.

01:30:36.870 --> 01:30:41.850
his reading mentor had worked
in the automobile industry.

01:30:41.850 --> 01:30:46.370
And guess what this young man
does now, he works as a lobbyist

01:30:46.370 --> 01:30:50.130
for the National Automobile
Manufacturing Association.

01:30:50.130 --> 01:30:53.890
So this mentor had an impact
that has influenced his life,

01:30:53.890 --> 01:30:58.180
influenced his career path and
now he was ready to give back.

01:30:58.180 --> 01:31:01.210
So bringing this-- this shared
reading experiences that build

01:31:01.210 --> 01:31:03.670
that kind of confidence
that build that kind

01:31:03.670 --> 01:31:04.970
of background knowledge

01:31:04.970 --> 01:31:08.190
and strengthen those
socioemotional skills

01:31:08.190 --> 01:31:12.480
that we all want kids
to have is so critical.

01:31:12.480 --> 01:31:16.970
But there's so much more
that we felt like we could do

01:31:16.970 --> 01:31:19.190
through the shared
reading experiences

01:31:19.190 --> 01:31:22.790
and the opportunities
to engage kids.

01:31:22.790 --> 01:31:26.370
One of our-- One of Everybody
Wins additional partnerships

01:31:26.370 --> 01:31:31.950
in the city focuses on
bringing authors to schools

01:31:31.950 --> 01:31:34.800
with the partnership with
An Open Book Foundation,

01:31:34.800 --> 01:31:38.820
which is a nonprofit here in DC
that takes advantage of the fact

01:31:38.820 --> 01:31:40.480
that DC is full of authors

01:31:40.480 --> 01:31:44.160
and that authors come
to DC all the time.

01:31:44.160 --> 01:31:47.690
And so, why not take them to
schools that are underresourced

01:31:47.690 --> 01:31:51.330
and might really benefit
from that opportunity.

01:31:51.330 --> 01:31:55.420
We're ready now, this is our
innovation, we're ready to take

01:31:55.420 --> 01:31:59.560
that step forward and not
just have authors come

01:31:59.560 --> 01:32:03.410
into the schools, you know,
here's an author, yay,

01:32:03.410 --> 01:32:06.590
here's a book, yay, I got a new
book and the author signed it.

01:32:06.590 --> 01:32:11.800
But to move that forward so that
we're continuing the learning

01:32:11.800 --> 01:32:15.080
after the experience so that
kids are doing their own

01:32:15.080 --> 01:32:17.540
writing, so that kids
are doing more research

01:32:17.540 --> 01:32:20.540
on what they've learned and
talked about with the author.

01:32:20.540 --> 01:32:24.460
And we're very excited to see
what's going to happen with that

01:32:24.460 --> 01:32:27.310
and how we can further
engage the school community

01:32:27.310 --> 01:32:28.880
in those opportunities
by involving parents,

01:32:28.880 --> 01:32:33.100
by involving parents, by
involving our reading mentors

01:32:33.100 --> 01:32:35.860
so that they are also getting
a chance to come and speak

01:32:35.860 --> 01:32:37.760
and talk about what
it is they do

01:32:37.760 --> 01:32:41.760
and what it is they are
excited about reading

01:32:41.760 --> 01:32:44.740
because it's an excited
adult reader

01:32:44.740 --> 01:32:48.150
that is an excellent
example for a kid.

01:32:48.150 --> 01:32:51.630
And seeing adults around
them choosing reading

01:32:51.630 --> 01:32:56.130
and choosing reading as a
fun activity is I don't how

01:32:56.130 --> 01:32:59.170
as we can replace that and
I think that's why Read

01:32:59.170 --> 01:33:02.500
Across America was-- is so
successful for so many years

01:33:02.500 --> 01:33:07.230
because if an adult in your life
is willing to put on a crazy hat

01:33:07.230 --> 01:33:08.760
and spend time reading with you,

01:33:08.760 --> 01:33:11.200
then you know there's
something to that.

01:33:11.200 --> 01:33:13.470
And I'm hoping that
we'll be able to continue

01:33:13.470 --> 01:33:16.810
to find exciting entry
points like that for folks

01:33:16.810 --> 01:33:21.430
from all walks of life and that
we'll all be working together

01:33:21.430 --> 01:33:24.210
on this reading promotion
opportunities

01:33:24.210 --> 01:33:27.500
because it makes more
sense if we're all sharing

01:33:27.500 --> 01:33:29.600
that information and all kind

01:33:29.600 --> 01:33:32.470
of supporting each other
as we do this work.

01:33:32.470 --> 01:33:35.530
I love-- I love Reach
Out and Read.

01:33:35.530 --> 01:33:38.320
I'm so glad that you mentioned
that Benita because I think

01:33:38.320 --> 01:33:41.730
that that's one of the strongest
reading promotion programs

01:33:41.730 --> 01:33:43.030
that's out there.

01:33:43.030 --> 01:33:47.020
