01:40:33.590 --> 01:40:35.430
and it is really
already, you know--

01:40:35.430 --> 01:40:37.010
I think the partnership
between laundromats

01:40:37.010 --> 01:40:38.310
and libraries is
really interesting

01:40:38.310 --> 01:40:40.430
because already laundromats are

01:40:40.430 --> 01:40:42.090
in some ways community
anchors, right?

01:40:42.090 --> 01:40:48.340
And so the fit is really easy
to find the connections with.

01:40:48.340 --> 01:40:51.180
Thanks for sharing that word.

01:40:51.180 --> 01:40:52.810
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield: Thank you.

01:40:52.810 --> 01:40:54.110
Other questions?

01:40:54.110 --> 01:40:55.950
&gt;&gt; So I have a related question.

01:40:55.950 --> 01:40:57.840
This laundromat thing
is fascinating.

01:40:57.840 --> 01:40:59.540
So I'm interested in hearing--

01:40:59.540 --> 01:41:02.240
I'm taking Laura's question
a little bit further.

01:41:02.240 --> 01:41:05.220
Is the outreach-- and I
understand you define that kind

01:41:05.220 --> 01:41:08.220
of liberally but is that meant
to say within the laundromat

01:41:08.220 --> 01:41:10.240
and is it a space construction?

01:41:10.240 --> 01:41:13.680
Is there some kind of hope to
convert to Library cards or move

01:41:13.680 --> 01:41:15.920
to a Library for a
different kind of programming?

01:41:15.920 --> 01:41:17.630
Can you talk about
that a little bit?

01:41:17.630 --> 01:41:18.930
Thank you.

01:41:18.930 --> 01:41:20.610
&gt;&gt; Allister Chang: So we've
been doing free laundry days

01:41:20.610 --> 01:41:22.040
with sponsorship.

01:41:22.040 --> 01:41:24.870
It's a great way to build new
sponsorships with corporations

01:41:24.870 --> 01:41:28.700
that haven't funded
libraries in the past.

01:41:28.700 --> 01:41:35.720
Four hours free laundry, laundry
is 5, $10 a-- $5 a load usually,

01:41:35.720 --> 01:41:38.350
so it's-- it adds
up for families.

01:41:38.350 --> 01:41:41.270
One connection that I found
that's really interesting is a

01:41:41.270 --> 01:41:44.740
lot of the kids say-- have said
that they are embarrassed to go

01:41:44.740 --> 01:41:46.090
to school if their
laundry is not clean

01:41:46.090 --> 01:41:48.500
so there's other dignity
elements to it too.

01:41:48.500 --> 01:41:54.060
Well with free laundry what we
do is partner with a laundromat,

01:41:54.060 --> 01:41:56.280
provide free laundry for four
hours we usually have three,

01:41:56.280 --> 01:41:58.030
four hour line outside
the block.

01:41:58.030 --> 01:41:59.620
Invite local organizations
to come.

01:41:59.620 --> 01:42:03.210
Sign people up for their
programs and sign people up,

01:42:03.210 --> 01:42:04.510
in order to get free laundry,

01:42:04.510 --> 01:42:05.810
you have to have a
library card, right?

01:42:05.810 --> 01:42:08.700
And that's an easy another
nudge restriction that we put

01:42:08.700 --> 01:42:12.210
on which I know is not the most.

01:42:12.210 --> 01:42:14.550
It's a little bit of the
eager piece but I think

01:42:14.550 --> 01:42:19.750
if we have a clown there it's
kind of-- it's fun [laughter].

01:42:19.750 --> 01:42:23.200
&gt;&gt; So my question is to Dr. Roy

01:42:23.200 --> 01:42:24.730
but really could be
answered by anyone.

01:42:24.730 --> 01:42:29.610
I still appreciated or
comments about being careful

01:42:29.610 --> 01:42:32.770
that we're not colonizing that
when we're trying to partner

01:42:32.770 --> 01:42:35.450
with organizations
and communities

01:42:35.450 --> 01:42:38.520
that we're not bringing
our own values.

01:42:38.520 --> 01:42:42.060
And I see the challenge of that
is that we're bringing support

01:42:42.060 --> 01:42:44.710
to a community because we
believe that we have solutions

01:42:44.710 --> 01:42:48.380
that can support that community
but if we're not really partners

01:42:48.380 --> 01:42:50.600
in listening and apart of that,

01:42:50.600 --> 01:42:52.930
we very much are just placing
our values on top of them.

01:42:52.930 --> 01:42:54.230
So really appreciate of that.

01:42:54.230 --> 01:42:58.230
And I'm just wondering what has
worked or not worked in for you

01:42:58.230 --> 01:43:01.230
or for anyone else in making
community partnerships

01:43:01.230 --> 01:43:03.660
that really truly partner
with the community?

01:43:03.660 --> 01:43:04.960
&gt;&gt; Loreiene Roy: Great.

01:43:04.960 --> 01:43:06.260
That's a great question.

01:43:06.260 --> 01:43:07.560
I guess I'll use an example.

01:43:07.560 --> 01:43:09.860
Some years ago, the
State Library

01:43:09.860 --> 01:43:12.180
in Arizona had a
supplemental grant

01:43:12.180 --> 01:43:16.400
to their Bill &amp; Melinda Gates
funded technology centers.

01:43:16.400 --> 01:43:18.810
And so they provided
some funding

01:43:18.810 --> 01:43:21.990
to a higher community
tech in six

01:43:21.990 --> 01:43:24.900
or eight tribal settings
in Arizona.

01:43:24.900 --> 01:43:29.290
Hopi Reservation, there
was one on-- let's see--

01:43:29.290 --> 01:43:31.700
I think Tony Odom
[assumed spelling], there--

01:43:31.700 --> 01:43:34.010
so different locations,
travel locations.

01:43:34.010 --> 01:43:36.430
And I was the evaluator
for the project.

01:43:36.430 --> 01:43:41.070
And each site also
had a student intern

01:43:41.070 --> 01:43:42.890
from the University of Arizona.

01:43:42.890 --> 01:43:45.690
And so I got to meet with
all of the technology people,

01:43:45.690 --> 01:43:47.480
all the community people.

01:43:47.480 --> 01:43:50.600
I remember going to a
chapter house on Navajo

01:43:50.600 --> 01:43:54.570
and Navajo woman, then a woman
sat next to me very quietly

01:43:54.570 --> 01:43:57.590
and then pushed something toward
me, and it was a huge notebook,

01:43:57.590 --> 01:43:59.270
and it was filled with all

01:43:59.270 --> 01:44:02.290
of the things she had
learned to do at that center.

01:44:02.290 --> 01:44:05.380
And she had started for
the first time her own way

01:44:05.380 --> 01:44:08.920
of earning money was to
produce a graduation cards.

01:44:08.920 --> 01:44:11.830
And she learned Photoshop
and she learned how to print.

01:44:11.830 --> 01:44:14.440
And she didn't say a word
but she showed me everything.

01:44:14.440 --> 01:44:17.690
And so I got to hear what
patrons did at those sites.

01:44:17.690 --> 01:44:20.360
But speaking with the students,
I also got to learn a little bit

01:44:20.360 --> 01:44:22.490
about the motivation,
more about the motivation

01:44:22.490 --> 01:44:25.390
of why did they volunteer
to go and work

01:44:25.390 --> 01:44:28.290
in support a community
tech person from

01:44:28.290 --> 01:44:29.670
and their own travel community

01:44:29.670 --> 01:44:32.090
and that students
were nonnative.

01:44:32.090 --> 01:44:34.370
Anyway the first student who
want to speak to me, she said,

01:44:34.370 --> 01:44:36.330
I need 20 minutes of the hour.

01:44:36.330 --> 01:44:39.400
And what she talked about is
what she felt she should have

01:44:39.400 --> 01:44:41.550
experienced but didn't.

01:44:41.550 --> 01:44:43.410
She says, I should
have been brought

01:44:43.410 --> 01:44:47.530
into the sacred religious
experiences I want--

01:44:47.530 --> 01:44:49.760
and her demands were great.

01:44:49.760 --> 01:44:52.150
And I had already spoken to
the people of those sites,

01:44:52.150 --> 01:44:53.450
so I kind of had a heads

01:44:53.450 --> 01:44:55.340
up of what the students
are going to say.

01:44:55.340 --> 01:44:57.010
And I said, so why
did you want this?

01:44:57.010 --> 01:45:00.240
And she says, well, my dad
was an Indian house service

01:45:00.240 --> 01:45:01.710
physician in 20 years ago.

01:45:01.710 --> 01:45:03.710
That was his experience.

01:45:03.710 --> 01:45:06.420
And then another
young student said--

01:45:06.420 --> 01:45:07.730
and then they, they
had complaints.

01:45:07.730 --> 01:45:09.640
They said, you know, I showed
up on the day I was supposed

01:45:09.640 --> 01:45:10.940
to be there and nothing
happened.

01:45:10.940 --> 01:45:12.530
No one knew I was coming.

01:45:12.530 --> 01:45:15.260
And at-- so that was
a common experience.

01:45:15.260 --> 01:45:17.740
But I knew one of the
students had been a star.

01:45:17.740 --> 01:45:19.040
And that they-- they
didn't know.

01:45:19.040 --> 01:45:21.220
I'd already heard
from their sites.

01:45:21.220 --> 01:45:22.950
And we got to this
student and I said,

01:45:22.950 --> 01:45:24.250
so what was your experience?

01:45:24.250 --> 01:45:25.550
She says, oh, like
everyone else.

01:45:25.550 --> 01:45:27.710
I went on the day I was supposed
to and no one was there,

01:45:27.710 --> 01:45:29.810
she said, but I went
the next day.

01:45:29.810 --> 01:45:32.260
And she said, then I
went the following week.

01:45:32.260 --> 01:45:35.140
And what she did was her
expectations were she was there

01:45:35.140 --> 01:45:36.440
to help.

01:45:36.440 --> 01:45:39.510
And she was not there to
gain some inside track.

01:45:39.510 --> 01:45:41.900
So, a part was the motivation.

01:45:41.900 --> 01:45:44.680
I think that many gifts come

01:45:44.680 --> 01:45:47.240
from being involved
in community level.

01:45:47.240 --> 01:45:49.910
But it's not something you
can say, I'm going to do this,

01:45:49.910 --> 01:45:53.090
so I'm going to cherry pick
some cultural experience

01:45:53.090 --> 01:45:55.520
so I can talk about
it in 20 more years.

01:45:55.520 --> 01:45:56.820
So, you know, I have--

01:45:56.820 --> 01:45:59.780
one of the books I've
read in there is a chapter

01:45:59.780 --> 01:46:01.970
on examining one's motivation

01:46:01.970 --> 01:46:05.570
and everyone needs
to do that as well.

01:46:05.570 --> 01:46:07.740
So does that help answer
the question a little bit?

01:46:07.740 --> 01:46:09.190
OK. Thanks.

01:46:09.190 --> 01:46:10.630
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield: As you
can see we've opened the floor

01:46:10.630 --> 01:46:14.590
to everybody, the first
panel and the second panel.

01:46:14.590 --> 01:46:19.160
OK. Other questions?

01:46:20.490 --> 01:46:23.250
None? Yes sir?

01:46:23.250 --> 01:46:25.060
&gt;&gt; This is a question
for anybody,

01:46:25.060 --> 01:46:29.070
but maybe Allister
would be the best or--

01:46:29.070 --> 01:46:31.080
you know, I come mostly from
an international background.

01:46:31.080 --> 01:46:33.560
When you travel around the
world you hear ministers

01:46:33.560 --> 01:46:36.700
and librarians say-- talk
about a reading culture.

01:46:36.700 --> 01:46:40.010
So even in the golf for example,
they are burrowed with people

01:46:40.010 --> 01:46:41.750
who are quite wealthy.

01:46:41.750 --> 01:46:43.890
So we don't really have a
reading culture whereas we go

01:46:43.890 --> 01:46:47.270
to Russia for example, even the
relatively poor people are--

01:46:47.270 --> 01:46:48.810
they're great readers.

01:46:48.810 --> 01:46:51.740
Is there anything in this
idea of a reading culture

01:46:51.740 --> 01:46:55.560
or is it just as Dr. Krashen
said, you know, if you're poor,

01:46:55.560 --> 01:46:58.700
you don't read and if you're
not poor, you read more.

01:46:58.700 --> 01:47:02.680
Or, is there a body
research on that

01:47:02.680 --> 01:47:06.490
and is it relevant
to the United States?

01:47:06.490 --> 01:47:11.280
&gt;&gt; Stephen Krashen: I think
it's unfair to ask question

01:47:11.280 --> 01:47:14.600
because so many people do
not have access to books.

01:47:14.600 --> 01:47:18.870
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield: Could
you come to the podium?

01:47:18.870 --> 01:47:21.120
&gt;&gt; Stephen Krashen: This
is good for my career.

01:47:21.120 --> 01:47:23.770
Wonderful.

01:47:23.770 --> 01:47:26.410
If they have access to books
and they're still not reading,

01:47:26.410 --> 01:47:28.750
we can talk about the
absence of reading culture.

01:47:28.750 --> 01:47:31.350
But as James Patterson, which
I just quoted and pointed out,

01:47:31.350 --> 01:47:34.550
it may very well be the case
that nonreaders are simply those

01:47:34.550 --> 01:47:36.830
who haven't found
the right books yet.

01:47:36.830 --> 01:47:38.130
Great study.

01:47:38.130 --> 01:47:41.510
I would like to see replicated
in the laundromat was called

01:47:41.510 --> 01:47:43.080
"Spiderman in the Library."

01:47:43.080 --> 01:47:44.560
I forgot the author's name.

01:47:44.560 --> 01:47:46.630
They put comic books
in the library

01:47:46.630 --> 01:47:50.140
for junior high school children,
did not allow them to circulate,

01:47:50.140 --> 01:47:52.290
they had to go to the
library to read the comic.

01:47:52.290 --> 01:47:54.820
Library traffic went up doubled.

01:47:54.820 --> 01:47:58.460
Books taken out went up
30% in a very short time.

01:47:58.460 --> 01:48:00.560
When we bring in
books, they really,

01:48:00.560 --> 01:48:02.630
really, really want to read.

01:48:02.630 --> 01:48:05.540
And the best thing out now
for young people, comic books

01:48:05.540 --> 01:48:08.730
and graphic novels, no question.

01:48:08.730 --> 01:48:11.060
One of the great things
about being on the airplane,

01:48:11.060 --> 01:48:13.680
you get to catch up
on the marvel movies.

01:48:13.680 --> 01:48:15.510
Oh my gosh.

01:48:15.510 --> 01:48:18.920
Wonder Woman, Black Panther,

01:48:18.920 --> 01:48:22.730
serious philosophical
discussions.

01:48:22.730 --> 01:48:25.180
Wonder Woman is about
the nature of evil.

01:48:25.180 --> 01:48:26.810
I'm going to spoil it for you.

01:48:26.810 --> 01:48:29.590
Black Panther is on
the nature of justice.

01:48:29.590 --> 01:48:30.890
How do we do this?

01:48:30.890 --> 01:48:33.180
Is it correct when you
are born into wealth,

01:48:33.180 --> 01:48:35.390
when you're given it,
what is your obligation?

01:48:35.390 --> 01:48:38.470
OK. These are heavy things
and that's what people--

01:48:38.470 --> 01:48:42.490
it's framed in such a brilliant
way that people get involved

01:48:42.490 --> 01:48:44.240
in literature and reading.

01:48:44.240 --> 01:48:47.280
So, let's ask the
question when we've--

01:48:47.280 --> 01:48:50.950
about reading cultures when
we solve the access problem.

01:48:50.950 --> 01:48:52.750
Great question.

01:48:52.750 --> 01:48:58.750
[ Inaudible ]

01:48:58.750 --> 01:49:00.750
&gt;&gt; Deborah Taylor: That's
really an important question

01:49:00.750 --> 01:49:03.710
because I remember
hearing that commercial,

01:49:03.710 --> 01:49:06.210
read to your child
15 minutes a day,

01:49:06.210 --> 01:49:09.650
and I used to think
nobody ever read to me.

01:49:09.650 --> 01:49:12.060
But my grandmother
was a storyteller.

01:49:12.060 --> 01:49:14.290
And so it's not so much
just the culture of reading,

01:49:14.290 --> 01:49:16.290
is it a culture of storytelling?

01:49:16.290 --> 01:49:17.760
And how do you incorporate

01:49:17.760 --> 01:49:21.030
that so those stories are
captured and passed down?

01:49:21.030 --> 01:49:25.410
So one of the things that we do
with family reading circles is

01:49:25.410 --> 01:49:29.170
when we close out-- sometimes
we have a visiting illustrator,

01:49:29.170 --> 01:49:31.250
sometimes we have
a visiting author.

01:49:31.250 --> 01:49:33.750
But sometimes we have
a visiting storyteller.

01:49:33.750 --> 01:49:35.190
Because one of the
things that we--

01:49:35.190 --> 01:49:37.680
that if you observe
how parents interact

01:49:37.680 --> 01:49:39.360
with their children now,

01:49:39.360 --> 01:49:41.900
they are always giving
them directions.

01:49:41.900 --> 01:49:44.420
They are seldom really
telling them things

01:49:44.420 --> 01:49:46.200
or storytelling anymore.

01:49:46.200 --> 01:49:49.370
My grandmother told me
stories constantly whenever we

01:49:49.370 --> 01:49:50.670
were together.

01:49:50.670 --> 01:49:51.970
So I think the culture

01:49:51.970 --> 01:49:55.340
of storytelling is the one
we want to really encourage.

01:49:55.340 --> 01:49:58.500
And if it means writing down
those stories and capturing them

01:49:58.500 --> 01:50:00.440
and sharing them,
then that, I think,

01:50:00.440 --> 01:50:05.170
helps with the whole
prospect of a reading culture.

01:50:05.170 --> 01:50:06.470
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield: Thank you.

01:50:06.470 --> 01:50:07.770
&gt;&gt; Stephen Krashen: Can I
add a friendly amendment?

01:50:07.770 --> 01:50:09.070
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield: What?

01:50:09.070 --> 01:50:10.370
&gt;&gt; Stephen Krashen: A
friendly short amendment

01:50:10.370 --> 01:50:11.970
to your wonderful comment?

01:50:11.970 --> 01:50:14.880
We-- Stories are what
makes the world go round.

01:50:14.880 --> 01:50:18.490
All-- Everybody like
stories constantly.

01:50:18.490 --> 01:50:21.810
Let me give you some
advice for your social life.

01:50:21.810 --> 01:50:24.700
If you're invited to a party
and you don't know anybody,

01:50:24.700 --> 01:50:27.320
watch three lady's movies.

01:50:27.320 --> 01:50:30.710
You can always go up to someone
and say, I just saw, you know,

01:50:30.710 --> 01:50:33.690
Iron Man 26, you
know, or whatever.

01:50:33.690 --> 01:50:36.720
And, you know, Iron
Ladies, Iron Lady,

01:50:36.720 --> 01:50:39.620
and you can get a
reasonable conversation going

01:50:39.620 --> 01:50:42.140
because people want
to know about stories.

01:50:42.140 --> 01:50:44.680
We interpret our
lives as a narrative

01:50:44.680 --> 01:50:46.500
where we are the protagonists.

01:50:46.500 --> 01:50:47.800
So, absolutely.

01:50:47.800 --> 01:50:49.500
&gt;&gt; Thanks for that.

01:50:49.500 --> 01:50:50.800
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

01:50:50.800 --> 01:50:52.100
&gt;&gt; Rachel Walker: I think
it is an important addition,

01:50:52.100 --> 01:50:55.380
but one of the things that has
worried me about when we talk

01:50:55.380 --> 01:50:59.580
about creating a culture
around reading is I've asked

01:50:59.580 --> 01:51:02.180
so many people over the
years, are you a reader?

01:51:02.180 --> 01:51:04.100
Do you consider yourself
a reader?

01:51:04.100 --> 01:51:05.490
Do you like reading?

01:51:05.490 --> 01:51:07.580
And most of the time,
the answer I get is no.

01:51:07.580 --> 01:51:09.140
I don't like reading.

01:51:09.140 --> 01:51:10.440
I don't like reading at all.

01:51:10.440 --> 01:51:11.760
And then I said,
but do you read?

01:51:11.760 --> 01:51:13.060
What do you read?

01:51:13.060 --> 01:51:14.360
Oh yeah, I read all the time.

01:51:14.360 --> 01:51:15.660
I read newspapers.

01:51:15.660 --> 01:51:16.960
I read this.

01:51:16.960 --> 01:51:18.260
I read journals.

01:51:18.260 --> 01:51:19.560
I read-- they don't
read fiction.

01:51:19.560 --> 01:51:23.250
So I don't want to-- I totally
agree about storytelling

01:51:23.250 --> 01:51:25.920
but my concern is
is that we've--

01:51:25.920 --> 01:51:28.760
read to your child 15 minutes
a day, gives you that image

01:51:28.760 --> 01:51:31.470
of I'm sharing a Dr.
Seuss book with you

01:51:31.470 --> 01:51:34.250
or I'm sharing a story with you.

01:51:34.250 --> 01:51:37.620
And I don't want to leave
out those folks who come

01:51:37.620 --> 01:51:40.770
at it in a different way.

01:51:40.770 --> 01:51:42.910
&gt;&gt; Stephen Krashen: There is
research, there's research

01:51:42.910 --> 01:51:44.590
on gossip and stories.

01:51:44.590 --> 01:51:47.990
Most of what goes on in
newspapers is human interest.

01:51:47.990 --> 01:51:50.480
What Albert Einstein
talked to other physicists,

01:51:50.480 --> 01:51:53.600
they talked about their personal
lives, stories and gossip.

01:51:53.600 --> 01:51:56.200
I still maintain stories as
what makes the world go round.

01:51:56.200 --> 01:51:59.900
&gt;&gt; Lesley Farmer: And then
just to even broaden it more,

01:51:59.900 --> 01:52:02.100
I think you can also
talk about song.

01:52:02.100 --> 01:52:06.730
So just recently words on
literature where, you know,

01:52:06.730 --> 01:52:10.870
Bob Dylan won earlier,
you know, Ira Gershwin.

01:52:10.870 --> 01:52:15.600
So, again, these are gateways,
storytelling, the songs,

01:52:15.600 --> 01:52:18.930
the rhythms that we have are
all gateways to literacy.

01:52:18.930 --> 01:52:21.480
&gt;&gt; Deborah Taylor: I've heard
parents say that their children

01:52:21.480 --> 01:52:25.690
or there's-- particularly,
this occurs with boys,

01:52:25.690 --> 01:52:28.140
that all he wants to
do is study baseball

01:52:28.140 --> 01:52:29.880
or basketball statistics.

01:52:29.880 --> 01:52:34.200
And I tell them, he is creating
the narrative in his head

01:52:34.200 --> 01:52:35.870
from those statistics.

01:52:35.870 --> 01:52:37.360
He is a reader.

01:52:37.360 --> 01:52:41.780
But he is going after his
story land, his narrative

01:52:41.780 --> 01:52:45.260
in a different way than
I might who, you know,

01:52:45.260 --> 01:52:48.300
with a voracious reader
of trashy romance novels.

01:52:48.300 --> 01:52:50.630
So it just really does--

01:52:50.630 --> 01:52:51.930
you know, you really have

01:52:51.930 --> 01:52:53.470
to respect the reader
where the reader is.

01:52:53.470 --> 01:52:55.840
And then I think
people see themselves

01:52:55.840 --> 01:52:57.140
as part of that culture.

01:52:57.140 --> 01:52:58.440
&gt;&gt; Lois Bridges: Yeah.

01:52:58.440 --> 01:53:02.210
Just speaking to the scholarly
culture, I just wanted

01:53:02.210 --> 01:53:05.090
to mention one of the most
significant studies of all

01:53:05.090 --> 01:53:09.110
at the University of
Nevada, Mariah Evans,

01:53:09.110 --> 01:53:14.440
who's a sociologist, found
that even just 12 books

01:53:14.440 --> 01:53:18.500
in the home created what she
called a scholarly culture.

01:53:18.500 --> 01:53:21.700
And I think what she meant
is that if you have books

01:53:21.700 --> 01:53:24.550
in the home, you're
talking about the books,

01:53:24.550 --> 01:53:25.850
you're reading the books.

01:53:25.850 --> 01:53:27.370
You're sharing the
books with each other.

01:53:27.370 --> 01:53:33.880
And we find that parents who may
not have had access to literacy

01:53:33.880 --> 01:53:36.970
as children themselves, if their
children are bringing books

01:53:36.970 --> 01:53:40.730
home, then they're
learning to read.

01:53:40.730 --> 01:53:44.640
The children, you have the books
in the home, are reading allowed

01:53:44.640 --> 01:53:46.170
to their younger siblings.

01:53:46.170 --> 01:53:50.410
So you've-- it's-- the
talk as everyone has seen

01:53:50.410 --> 01:53:53.610
around the books, that is
so critically important.

01:53:53.610 --> 01:53:56.330
And also, by the
way reading allowed

01:53:56.330 --> 01:53:59.000
to children is so important.

01:53:59.000 --> 01:54:03.750
We know, but again, it's the
talk about the read allowed,

01:54:03.750 --> 01:54:06.680
you know, that bringing out
the child's personal engagement

01:54:06.680 --> 01:54:08.900
with the book that
really makes a difference.

01:54:08.900 --> 01:54:15.260
So, in the end, it all comes
back again to access to books.

01:54:15.260 --> 01:54:18.520
If you have access to
books, anything is possible.

01:54:18.520 --> 01:54:23.080
&gt;&gt; Loreiene Roy: I'll just
add a couple of things.

01:54:23.080 --> 01:54:24.380
When we run--

01:54:24.380 --> 01:54:25.680
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield:
In the podium.

01:54:25.680 --> 01:54:26.980
&gt;&gt; Loreiene Roy: OK.

01:54:26.980 --> 01:54:28.280
When we run the reading
club for native kids,

01:54:28.280 --> 01:54:31.430
I would go to travel schools and
we would certainly read books

01:54:31.430 --> 01:54:32.910
but we always did
the storytelling too.

01:54:32.910 --> 01:54:36.620
And I know that that the
secret to getting native kids

01:54:36.620 --> 01:54:38.860
to pay attention is
to say you're going

01:54:38.860 --> 01:54:40.570
to tell them a ghost story.

01:54:40.570 --> 01:54:42.130
And you then tell
them ghost stories

01:54:42.130 --> 01:54:45.280
that you yourself experienced
and they're really true.

01:54:45.280 --> 01:54:47.950
And then I always told
the true ghost stories.

01:54:47.950 --> 01:54:50.520
And-- But for native kids,
one difference would be that--

01:54:50.520 --> 01:54:52.840
just like storytelling
is social,

01:54:52.840 --> 01:54:55.330
reading is very social
for native children.

01:54:55.330 --> 01:54:58.360
And board books, you think
of board books as a bit--

01:54:58.360 --> 01:55:01.060
books that you give babies,
but we found that kids

01:55:01.060 --> 01:55:02.770
up to fourth grade would
use the board books

01:55:02.770 --> 01:55:04.070
because they would sit

01:55:04.070 --> 01:55:05.990
with other children especially
younger ones and they would go

01:55:05.990 --> 01:55:07.510
through the books together.

01:55:07.510 --> 01:55:10.360
And they would form their
own little pads of reading.

01:55:10.360 --> 01:55:12.880
They knew especially in those
schools where kid had reading--

01:55:12.880 --> 01:55:15.390
kids had reading level to know

01:55:15.390 --> 01:55:17.450
that they knew everybody's
reading level

01:55:17.450 --> 01:55:19.400
and they would help each
other select the books.

01:55:19.400 --> 01:55:20.700
Like oh, no, no, no.

01:55:20.700 --> 01:55:22.000
You want to read this,
you want to read that.

01:55:22.000 --> 01:55:25.410
So reading as a culture
is very communal just

01:55:25.410 --> 01:55:29.290
like storytelling is communal
with native schools especially.

01:55:29.290 --> 01:55:30.590
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield:

01:55:30.590 --> 01:55:32.850
I just have one comment
I'd like to make.

01:55:32.850 --> 01:55:36.580
I need to speak up for the
adults, which is nobody is.

01:55:36.580 --> 01:55:42.190
What we found in the
Barbara Bush Foundation,

01:55:42.190 --> 01:55:46.610
we funded about a thousand
programs over the years.

01:55:46.610 --> 01:55:50.360
Many parents who were not
interested in investing

01:55:50.360 --> 01:55:54.140
in themselves for variety
of reasons mostly none

01:55:54.140 --> 01:55:58.230
of them very good about
self-concept care to learn

01:55:58.230 --> 01:56:01.040
to read so they could
read to their children.

01:56:01.040 --> 01:56:04.770
I agree with you, it's the
conversation that matters,

01:56:04.770 --> 01:56:07.410
but I really-- I worked

01:56:07.410 --> 01:56:10.200
in programs before I've
run a foundation, you know,

01:56:10.200 --> 01:56:12.860
during the great society
stuff in prisoners

01:56:12.860 --> 01:56:15.480
and in homeless shelters
and whatever.

01:56:15.480 --> 01:56:21.330
I don't-- we did family
literacy programs in prisons.

01:56:21.330 --> 01:56:23.690
I don't think it's
going to sound crazy.

01:56:23.690 --> 01:56:25.890
I don't think I ever run into
a parent that didn't want

01:56:25.890 --> 01:56:30.750
to be able to learn to read, to
read a book to his or her child.

01:56:30.750 --> 01:56:34.080
And reading in this context
doesn't necessarily mean

01:56:34.080 --> 01:56:36.320
that you have to have
fantastically developed

01:56:36.320 --> 01:56:37.900
reading skills.

01:56:37.900 --> 01:56:42.610
It's be with the child, turn
the pages, tell the story.

01:56:42.610 --> 01:56:48.500
And that often insights a desire
to learn to read on the part

01:56:48.500 --> 01:56:52.500
of the adults because it's for
the relationship with the child.

01:56:52.500 --> 01:56:53.800
I just throw that in.

01:56:53.800 --> 01:56:56.580
Sorry, go ahead.

01:56:56.580 --> 01:57:01.450
&gt;&gt; Hi. So my office,
we do museum education.

01:57:01.450 --> 01:57:04.800
And so I'm listening to all of
you and we're probably not going

01:57:04.800 --> 01:57:07.560
to get books into
children's hands as much,

01:57:07.560 --> 01:57:10.490
we're doing more
digital outreach.

01:57:10.490 --> 01:57:14.310
Is there-- Can you recommend,
do you have, just off the top

01:57:14.310 --> 01:57:17.940
of your head, maybe strategies
for what we should be creating

01:57:17.940 --> 01:57:21.160
or how maybe should we be
reaching out to parents,

01:57:21.160 --> 01:57:23.010
should we be reaching
out to libraries?

01:57:23.010 --> 01:57:27.650
What's our best approach
to help kids?

01:57:27.650 --> 01:57:32.220
&gt;&gt; Loreiene Roy: I'll just use
one example since this is just

01:57:32.220 --> 01:57:34.730
down the street the National
Museum American Indian.

01:57:34.730 --> 01:57:36.150
So I was involved with a group

01:57:36.150 --> 01:57:39.800
that created the first online
exhibits for the museum working

01:57:39.800 --> 01:57:41.900
with eight, nine
and 10-year-olds.

01:57:41.900 --> 01:57:45.880
And so, my job was to help
the children narrate a tour

01:57:45.880 --> 01:57:49.520
of the museum materials
on exhibit that we move

01:57:49.520 --> 01:57:51.230
from exhibition cases.

01:57:51.230 --> 01:57:54.380
We created 360 movies
of the objects,

01:57:54.380 --> 01:57:58.010
linked them to panoramic
views of the exhibit space.

01:57:58.010 --> 01:58:00.820
And then the kids narrated
the tour but we use

01:58:00.820 --> 01:58:04.330
that following a narrow
history model of asking.

01:58:04.330 --> 01:58:07.170
I asked the children to
describe who created the object,

01:58:07.170 --> 01:58:09.010
where were they from,
how did they created

01:58:09.010 --> 01:58:10.570
and for what purpose.

01:58:10.570 --> 01:58:12.720
And they used written
materials as well

01:58:12.720 --> 01:58:16.030
as their own cultural stories
to do the interpretation.

01:58:16.030 --> 01:58:18.880
So that was for the NMAI.

01:58:18.880 --> 01:58:21.990
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield:
Any other responses?

01:58:21.990 --> 01:58:24.540
&gt;&gt; Rachel Walker: So with
PBS and Reading Rockets,

01:58:24.540 --> 01:58:26.880
we are definitely
a digital platform.

01:58:26.880 --> 01:58:30.420
And so, we've done a lot at
looking at what that means

01:58:30.420 --> 01:58:32.580
and how is that really useful.

01:58:32.580 --> 01:58:35.910
And we found that one of
the things that is great is,

01:58:35.910 --> 01:58:38.900
of course, video because
videos are very accessible.

01:58:38.900 --> 01:58:41.260
You can tell a lot of
stories with video.

01:58:41.260 --> 01:58:44.570
But also we found that it
works even better if you take

01:58:44.570 --> 01:58:48.640
that video and you put it into
action so that if it's a digital

01:58:48.640 --> 01:58:51.780
and you're communicating with
folks all over the world,

01:58:51.780 --> 01:58:53.990
they can learn how
to use that video

01:58:53.990 --> 01:58:55.610
to the best that it can be used.

01:58:55.610 --> 01:58:57.990
So they share it with a
parent or to use it as part

01:58:57.990 --> 01:59:01.240
of the professional development
opportunity for a teacher.

01:59:01.240 --> 01:59:03.530
So it can't just-- we don't
want it to just be static

01:59:03.530 --> 01:59:06.400
and they're online, we know
people will find it and use it

01:59:06.400 --> 01:59:09.050
but to have that kind of
outreach in those opportunities

01:59:09.050 --> 01:59:11.520
where you're saying, here
are a lot of different ways

01:59:11.520 --> 01:59:15.030
that you can put it into
action in your community.

01:59:15.030 --> 01:59:16.330
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield:
Any other responses?

01:59:16.330 --> 01:59:19.200
OK. Next question.

01:59:19.200 --> 01:59:21.560
&gt;&gt; Hi. Well, I'm really
interested in Rachel

01:59:21.560 --> 01:59:22.940
and what you were
saying and you all--

01:59:22.940 --> 01:59:26.300
some of you all have alluded to
this with the power of process

01:59:26.300 --> 01:59:29.870
and children going from author
visits or a books experience

01:59:29.870 --> 01:59:33.000
and making their own narrative
and what that looks like.

01:59:33.000 --> 01:59:35.380
So I just wanted to know if you
could talk a little bit more

01:59:35.380 --> 01:59:40.990
about that that process.

01:59:40.990 --> 01:59:43.880
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield: You go.

01:59:43.880 --> 01:59:46.110
&gt;&gt; Rachel Walker: So
one of the reasons

01:59:46.110 --> 01:59:49.240
that I was really excited about
working with Everybody Wins

01:59:49.240 --> 01:59:52.610
and the idea of doing
more to engage kids

01:59:52.610 --> 01:59:54.020
to share reading experiences

01:59:54.020 --> 01:59:56.680
that were not necessarily
just one-on-one but looking

01:59:56.680 --> 01:59:58.690
at that kind of community
that you build

01:59:58.690 --> 02:00:01.070
when you're sharing a
book that's the same

02:00:01.070 --> 02:00:04.190
and sharing the experience of
getting to meet the author.

02:00:04.190 --> 02:00:07.560
For a couple of years, I spent
some time in a middle school

02:00:07.560 --> 02:00:11.620
and we decided that we
really needed to focus

02:00:11.620 --> 02:00:15.520
on helping students figure
out what motivated them

02:00:15.520 --> 02:00:17.180
as readers and writers.

02:00:17.180 --> 02:00:19.190
And we thought that one
thing that would really do

02:00:19.190 --> 02:00:23.010
that would be to introduce
them to a lot of writers.

02:00:23.010 --> 02:00:26.390
And, yes, it was actually
true that that work.

02:00:26.390 --> 02:00:32.090
So one year we had I think 14
author visits during a school

02:00:32.090 --> 02:00:35.660
year which was a tremendous
amount of effort on part

02:00:35.660 --> 02:00:38.290
of the teachers and
the librarians there.

02:00:38.290 --> 02:00:43.190
But what we saw was that
kids were and we ask them

02:00:43.190 --> 02:00:44.680
because we wanted to make sure.

02:00:44.680 --> 02:00:47.220
So we-- first we wanted to
know who do you want to meet,

02:00:47.220 --> 02:00:50.480
what authors are you interested
in, or what are your interests

02:00:50.480 --> 02:00:53.390
because it wasn't going to do
any good to bring an author

02:00:53.390 --> 02:00:56.330
that we hadn't prep the kids
for or that didn't have some

02:00:56.330 --> 02:00:58.620
of connection to what
they are already learning

02:00:58.620 --> 02:01:00.300
or working on in school.

02:01:00.300 --> 02:01:03.030
So to make it really
concentrated effort on figuring

02:01:03.030 --> 02:01:05.490
out how it fits in
to their daily lives

02:01:05.490 --> 02:01:07.990
because it's not
just necessarily

02:01:07.990 --> 02:01:10.330
that they're interested that's
going to be the motivation

02:01:10.330 --> 02:01:14.030
for them to get excited about
this but it's going to be kind

02:01:14.030 --> 02:01:15.930
of what they're existing
background knowledge is,

02:01:15.930 --> 02:01:17.950
so that they can take
it and go with it.

02:01:17.950 --> 02:01:21.150
So that's really what we look
at, the motivation factor

02:01:21.150 --> 02:01:23.460
but then also what
it is that we're--

02:01:23.460 --> 02:01:25.400
that they already have
that we can build on.

02:01:25.400 --> 02:01:27.950
And it-- I'm hoping
that it's going to work

02:01:27.950 --> 02:01:30.250
in elementary schools too.

02:01:34.210 --> 02:01:36.990
&gt;&gt; Deborah Taylor: The
Pratt library partnered

02:01:36.990 --> 02:01:39.420
with the Reginald Lewis Museum

02:01:39.420 --> 02:01:41.390
and the Baltimore
City public schools

02:01:41.390 --> 02:01:46.240
to run a book making
contest that we had funded

02:01:46.240 --> 02:01:47.980
from the Ezra Jack
Keats Foundation.

02:01:47.980 --> 02:01:50.260
They run the huge
one in New York.

02:01:50.260 --> 02:01:53.260
And so we were just starting out

02:01:53.260 --> 02:01:57.650
and this gave the students a
chance to write their stories

02:01:57.650 --> 02:01:59.540
to illustrate their stories.

02:01:59.540 --> 02:02:01.950
We did a teacher workshop,
so the teachers learned how

02:02:01.950 --> 02:02:04.030
to show them different ways

02:02:04.030 --> 02:02:07.070
of making the books
like anything else.

02:02:07.070 --> 02:02:10.260
We had one teacher that
caught fire with the idea.

02:02:10.260 --> 02:02:12.910
And she was teaching
graphics art, ends with this--

02:02:12.910 --> 02:02:17.570
all of these submissions from
her class and they worked

02:02:17.570 --> 02:02:21.230
on getting those
students to actually write

02:02:21.230 --> 02:02:25.610
and make graphic novels
from what they did.

02:02:25.610 --> 02:02:29.140
And then we have the
announcement of the winners

02:02:29.140 --> 02:02:31.060
at the Reginald Lewis Museum

02:02:31.060 --> 02:02:33.860
and then the library
displayed the winning and some

02:02:33.860 --> 02:02:35.160
of the other submission.

02:02:35.160 --> 02:02:37.250
So the three of us, there
were some kind of way

02:02:37.250 --> 02:02:41.120
that they're all three
institutions were engaged.

02:02:41.120 --> 02:02:43.270
&gt;&gt; Rachel Walker: And
I love the book making.

02:02:43.270 --> 02:02:46.480
One of the other things
that we did was we figured

02:02:46.480 --> 02:02:49.910
that kids were so excited
about what they were learning

02:02:49.910 --> 02:02:51.890
from authors that
they wanted to share

02:02:51.890 --> 02:02:53.750
that with all of
their classmates.

02:02:53.750 --> 02:02:57.640
So we created a podcast
that students then

02:02:57.640 --> 02:03:00.410
after the author visits
